Author: Ye Zhang#0760
Content:
Hi, I am still curious that why Cairo's performance is only 20-30% less than manually optimized circuits. From my understanding, Cairo works like TinyRAM. However, TinyRAM has a huge overhead and hasn't been used in practice. Is there any particular reason why Cairo is much better than TinyRAM? 
(1) Is that because the underlying ZKP system of Cairo is STARK? 
(2) Is that because Cairo requires continuous memory?  i.e. Programmer needs to code using continuous memory and thus Cairo can remove the permutation network inside the circuit.
(3) Is that because Cairo's AIR is much better than the instruction set in TinyRAM?
@Lior Goldberg @EliBenSasson 
When will it have more official whitepaper?

Author: spapini#3824
Content: All of the above. Builtins help a lot too. Whitepaper will be released soon

Author: Ye Zhang#0760
Content: Is there any concrete performance comparsion for Cairo? For example, proving time for a 2^30-sized Merkle tree and some other crypto benchmarks

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Note that Cairo is 20-30% worse than manually optimized circuits for programs that take advantage of builtins (so far this was true for all practical programs we had to deal with), but it's not true that for **any** program it'll be that efficient. By the way, once we moved to Cairo we actually *saved* cost over the manually optimized circuits, just because you could more easily implement algorithmic optimizations.

Author: EliBenSasson#9612
Content: @Ye Zhang to answer your questions: (1) No, there's also a STARK version of TinyRAM, part of the academic grade libSTARK library. (2) That's part of it, (3) Also part of it, though the instruction set of Cairo is actually smaller than that of tinyRAM, hence more efficient. Another point of view: TinyRAM started from a "standard" instruction set (one that doesn't take into account the algebraic constraints of building AIRs) and built constraints around it. Cairo came after handcrafting AIRs and is  a "just right" choice of an AIR that's powerful and agile enough to write programs in but also efficient in the size of the traces (and STARK proofs) that arise from it.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Try to answer the following question: what is the value at `[ap - 1]` at the end of the run? (`[ap-1]` is the last written cell).
For example, from the **prover** point of view, in the first code segment, it's going to be 5 because of the hint  (`sqrt(25)`). What can you say about this value from the **verifier** point of view? (recall that the verifier *does not* see the hint, and from its point of view, the hint can be replaced with any other hint)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Note that because of the line `[ap - 1] = [ap] * [ap]; ap++` the verifier does know that the square of the value is 25, but it doesn't have to be 5, it can be -5 as well (the second case ensures it's 5 and not -5)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
unsigned_div_rem is limited to 128 bit numbers (the exact requirement appears in the function documentation: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/cairo/common/math.cairo)
In order to work with 2048 bit numbers you'll have to split them into smaller chunks (e.g. 64-bit) and (for example) do long-multiplication.
This is similar to how you'd implement it in C, C# or Java (Python for example has arbitrary-length integers, so it's easier in Python).

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: In the future Cairo will have a BigInt library which will allow you to do such things

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Also, one possible optimizations is using Montgomery representation, where you don't have to do division.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Note that to work with exponentiation modulo a number you **must** perform modulo after each multiplication otherwise the numbers will become too big (it will give a wrong reason in languages such as Cairo, C and C#, and will never end in Python).

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: The fact consists of the program hash and the program output. Your smart contract will have the Cairo program hard-coded in it (think of it as an extension to the SC code) and will check that the fact talks about this particular program. Once you have verified the program you know that **moving** from root A to root B is consistent with the counts. Now you have to check that the current root was A (in the smart contract), and change it to B.

Content:
I will add a question on this, as I was trying to understand the same process as @Deleted User .
So, what is the difference then between just dumping a snapshot of e.g. a sidechain state on an L1 smart contract and dumping it with a stark proof? In the example of an exchange, wouldn't you still need to ask the exchange operator for the list of transactions that have been batched to verify that yours were executed correctly? Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Yes, exactly

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Using a proof guarantees that the on-chain state is *always* valid - in the voting example, if we see 5 yes votes it means that 5 digital signatures were verified. Other techniques do not have this strong guarantee. To verify that a specific balance, stored in Merkle root, was updated, you'll need to query the exchange to get the authentication path, but you don't need to *trust* the response you got, you can use the authentication path to make sure your balance is consistent with the Merkle root stored on Ethereum.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: See here for more detail on using validity proofs: https://medium.com/starkware/validity-proofs-vs-fraud-proofs-4ef8b4d3d87a

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
Another difference to what Lior described above is what determines the consensus - in a L2, the committed state on L1 is the true state of the L2 system.
Sidechains, usually, have their own consensus mechanisms that  determines the state of the system (e.g. longest chain rule). You can use proofs to verify the state of a sidechain on Ethereum, but it won't determine the state of the system.

Author: PB#8682
Content:
Hi. So I was going through the Signature Aggregation for Consensus example given here:
https://www.cairo-lang.org/from-voting-to-trustless-eth-bridges-via-signature-aggregation/

The example talks about verifying 100 out of 150 signatures. What I am unclear about is how Ethereum knows that the correct set of signers signed on the block (assuming that list is not hardcoded in the Cairo code and can change on Ethereum). Is there a way for Ethereum smart contract to verify that? A naive approach: 
- Cairo code computes the hash of signer list (which is input to the code) and puts this as an output
- The Ethereum smart contract recomputes the hash and then matches it with programOutput. 
The problem with above approach is that Cairo uses Pedersen hash, which is expensive on Ethereum. Am I missing something?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Indeed, you'd want to avoid using Pedersen on Ethereum or Keccak on Cairo.
The simplest solution is to pass the 150 keys to the Cairo program. Passing information between Cairo and Ethereum is not that expensive.
If you want to improve it (assuming the list of public keys doesn't change much): then you'll use a Pedersen hash. To avoid computing it on Ethereum you'll use a second Cairo program (let's call it "B", and let's call the original program "A") to prove that "The Pedersen hash of these specific 150 keys is x" (so that both the 150 keys and x are in program B's output). Then you'll store x on the smart contract's storage and pass it to program A (the one based on the voting tutorial) when signature verification is needed.
When the list changes, you'll invoke program B again.

Author: PB#8682
Content: Thanks a lot. This is a nice workaround.

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
Currently there is no lib functions for it. Implementing any hash function from the SHA family directly in Cairo is possible, but will be highly inefficient.

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
actually for (a) you need to be able to multiply a field element by scalar over the secp256k curve (you can read more about it here - https://github.com/ethereumbook/ethereumbook/blob/develop/04keys-addresses.asciidoc#public-keys), and it is also somewhat what you need for (b).
Currently 'verify_ecdsa_signature' does not support secp256 curve but only the curve that is used in the STARK proof, which is defined here https://docs.starkware.co/starkex-docs-v2/crypto/stark-curve.
Again, we plan to add support to secp256, but I don't have concrete timeline for that.

Author: nic619
Content:
Hi I had a question when going through the voting system example in Cairo doc. (plz let me know if this is not the right channel to ask questions about Cairo)

in process_votes code snippet:
```
func process_votes(...):
    ...
    # Update the public key dict.
    let public_key_tree_end = state.public_key_tree_end
    dict_update{dict_ptr=public_key_tree_end}(
        key=vote_info_ptr.voter_id,
        prev_value=vote_info_ptr.pub_key,
        new_value=0)
    ...
end
```

if I do not assign `state.public_key_tree_end` to `public_key_tree_end` and just pass in `state.public_key_tree_end` like this:

```
func process_votes(...):
    ...
    # Update the public key dict.
    dict_update{dict_ptr=state.public_key_tree_end}(
        key=vote_info_ptr.voter_id,
        prev_value=vote_info_ptr.pub_key,
        new_value=0)
    ...
end
```

I will get an `Implicit argument binding must be an identifier.` error.
I wonder what does it mean and what's the rule of thumb here when I encounter error like this again in the future?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Implicit arguments work as follows:
Let's say you have a function `foo{x}()`. The `{x}` means that `x` is added *both* as an argument and a return value. This means that in fact the function gets one value and returns one value.
The line `foo{x=y}()` calls the function foo with `y` as the argument and after `foo` returns it rebinds `y` to the returned value.
Therefore, implicit argument must be something that you can rebind later - you can't pass consts or things of the form `state.public_key_tree_end` just references.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: More importantly, note that after `dict_update{dict_ptr=public_key_tree_end}`, `public_key_tree_end` will not reference to `state.public_key_tree_end` anymore - it'll reference to the returned value of `dict_update`

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: (recall that Cairo's memory is immutable, so the value of `state.public_key_tree_end` can't change)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: You can read more here: https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/builtins.html#implicit-arguments

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: And about the mechanism of reference rebinding here: https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/consts.html#reference-rebinding

Author: nic619
Content:
> Therefore, implicit argument must be something that you can rebind later - you can't pass consts or things of the form state.public_key_tree_end just references.
This explains it very well. Thanks!

Author: anh_minh
Content: Hi! I am still quite a newbie in ZK proofs so sorry if the question is off-topic/stupid. I would like to try to write a STARK proof of computation of multiplication of a point on an elliptic curve "from scratch", using, say, OpenZKP. (e.g.  something similar to the manner of their Fibonacci number computations https://github.com/0xProject/OpenZKP/blob/master/crypto/stark/examples/small_fib.rs). So I was looking into the Cairo source code whether I can find something useful I could mimic and alter and I have a bunch of questions: On https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/crypto/starkware/crypto/signature/signature.py on line  163 def mimic_ec_mult_air()  - what does this function do? What is the shift-point?I see that we use it in the verification, but does is mean that the main reason we use this function and not ec_mult() is because the asserts inside and the shift point? I will be glad for any hints or suggestions for literature to read üôÇ

Author: ahmedali#6096
Content: @Lior Goldberg  AFAIK, ECDSA is a builtin signature algorithm in Cairo-lang. Does it also support Ed25519? Any suggestions also are welcomed üôÇ

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: The way we implement EC multiplication in the AIR is by using a cumulative sum of points. Since we want to avoid the zero point (to get an efficient AIR implementation), we start the sum not from zero but from a "fixed random" point, called the "shift point". So in fact we compute S + b0 * P + b1 * (2P) + b2 * (4P) + ... = S + xP instead of simply xP (where ...b2b1b0 is the binary representation of x). The difference between mimic_ec_mult_air() and ec_mult() is that  mimic_ec_mult_air() simulates exactly the same operations done by the AIR, so if for some reason we get the zero point along the computation, it'll raise an error.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: (this is rather technical and has to do with the way we chose to implement multiplication in the curve. If you choose other ways, these restrictions and technical details may not apply)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: By the way, what do you mean "from scratch"? Do you want to build AIRs? If so, I suggest reading: Vitalik's posts about STARKs, StarkWare's math blog posts (mainly about Arithmetization), and looking into bobbinth's (https://ethresear.ch/u/bobbinth/summary) work (e.g., AirScript)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: No, the ECDSA builtin is only ECDSA with a fixed curve. Supporting a general (not fixed) curve would've made the builtin more expensive. Moreover, Ed25519 requires a field other than the one used in Cairo, and in particular, this field is not STARK friendly. This means that Ed25519 will be much more expensive than the ECDSA builtin, even if we add a builtin for it.

Author: isk0996
Content:
Hi, 
Are there any open-source examples or docs for using Cairo with a standard NFT ERC721 contract? That would help me so much! 
Thanks in advance!

Author: perama
Content:
A standard Solidity ERC721 stores a lot of data on chain. For a roll-up, you want to only store the tiniest possible data on chain. All of the processing and checks and balances that an ERC721 would perform would instead be executed in Cairo.

So a redesign of the architecture is required, and interfacing with an existing 721 contract may not be beneficial. 

I haven't seen any open source NFT work. I understand that ImmutableX are forging the way using Cairo for NFTs, but are working in closed partnerships for now.

Author: perama
Content:
@Isk one idea might be to create a system where the NFTs are used frequently between different users. Low cost nonfungible tokens as the basis for a game, or interactive art system perhaps. In the event that a user wants to take their asset from the cairo-based L2 roll-up to L1, they can, incurring usual tx costs. 

That L1 contract could behave like a standard 721, where minting is conditional upon a check to the factRegistry to make sure the owner has the proper right to mint. Then the minted 721 is delivered to their L1 address

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
StarkNet will have a bridge that will allow working with (existing, L1) NFTs on L2 (but this is not something that exists now).
If the question is about Cairo in general, rather than StarkNet, then StarkEx2.0 is an example of a system that does that (and its L1 Solidity contracts are open-source, and the Cairo code is available and will become open-source soon), but it's a relatively complicated system.

Author: mheuer
Content:
Hi, python3.7 does not support ARM64 architecture (e.g. Apple Silicon M1 processors), but python3.9 supports it. Accordingly, devs with an Apple M1 MacBook or RaspberryPi can not use cairo-lang out of the box.
I made this into a github issue (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/issues/14)

However, there is the following workaround for Apple users (https://diewland.medium.com/how-to-install-python-3-7-on-macbook-m1-87c5b0fcb3b5)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
The error you get is `Wrong dict pointer supplied. Got 5:6, expected 5:3.`
It says that the dict_ptr suppied to `dict_read` is wrong. While `dict_read` expected to get `5:3` the code passed `5:6`.
The problem is that you have the line `dict=dict + DictAccess.SIZE` at the end of `iterate_dict`.
It should simply be `dict=dict` as `dict_read` already takes care of advancing the pointer.
This explain why instead of 3 you got 6 - it was advanced twice

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: (Also, you can improve the code by making the `dict` argument of `iterate_dict` an implicit arg. This will simplify `return(dict=dict)` to `return ()` and you won't have to pass it to the recursive call. If you call it `dict_ptr` instead of `dict` you'll also be able to remove the explicit `{dict_ptr=dict}` in `dict_read()`)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Oh, and don't forget to call `dict_finalize` at the very end - otherwise the code seems to work but it is not sound

Author: perama
Content:
So the proof of a program being executed is stored on Ethereum as a (verified) Fact 

The fact is stored on Ethereum inside a smart contract called the Registry

The registry can be found by syncing an Ethereum node and accessing the storage of that registry contract 

In this case the ethereum Ropsten testnet is being used. So you can download an Ethereum client and set the configuration to Ropsten, then sync. Once synced you can call the Registry contract with the details of the fact that you wish to check the existence of

http://localhost:8545

Or you can find some third party who runs an Ethereum Ropsten node as a service and you can get the url of their node from them

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
I suggest using `default_dict.cairo` instead of `dict_new()` since it doesn't require hints and therefore can be used in StarkNet (if you want to use Cairo in SHARP, rather than StarkNet, you can use both).
The difference is that all the values of a default dict always start from a default value. In order to initilize it, you simply call `dict_write()` (regular Cairo call, not a hint). At the end you finalize it using `default_dict_finalize`.
To call `default_dict_finalize`, pass (1) the pointer returned by default_dict_new (that is, the pointer before the changes), (2) the current pointer and (3) the same default value you passed to default_dict_new.
For example:
```
let (local my_dict_start) = default_dict_new(default_value=0)
# Create a different reference so that my_dict_start won't move.
let my_dict = my_dict_start
# The following line will change my_dict.
dict_read{dict_ptr=my_dict}(key=1234)
...
# Finalize the dict
default_dict_finalize(dict_accesses_start=my_dict_start, dict_accesses_end=my_dict, default_value=0)
```

Author: skintight
Content: hey, im a sorare user and i would like to know if theres a decentralized explorer like etherscan for stark or do we solely rely on sorare to see our cards? is there any way for me as a user to take control of my assets in a permissionless manner? like sending them to another address on L2? would i need to pay gas fees? is there an eth bridge? thanks.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Sorare is currently deployed on StarkEx, which is essentially a rollup for exchange type transactions. The StarkEx state is not directly exposed to the user. If the app uses on chain data then you can check the data yourself (and in the case of Validium, query one of the data availability committee members).  Note that In StarkNet, which is meant for general purpose contracts, there is a block explorer analogous to Etherscan.

Regarding your second question on "taking control of your assets", yes, in StarkEx the user can always withdraw his funds.  After your withdraw request (initiated on L2 or L1) is serviced you can call ‚ÄúwithdrawAndMint‚Äù on the StarkEx contract and have your assets minted on L1.  See our docs https://docs.starkware.co/starkex-v3/starkex-deep-dive/regular-flows/flows-for-off-chain-accounts/offchain-minting#step-3-withdraw-and-mint for a more detailed information on the flow.

They are working with a partner (Soraredata I believe) to get the data public

As FeedTheFed explained, the Data Committee will enable to free your assets in case of apocalyptic events. It is not permisionless but it is also the reason why Sorare has cheap txs.
> like sending them to another address on L2?
The tech enable it but it is at Sorare discretion to implement it
> would i need to pay gas fees?
It is at Sorare discretion
> is there an eth bridge?
Sorare is an L2. Everything is on Ethereum. So, you don't bring, you simply deposit to a smart contract

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Assuming that you have installed the cairo-lang package (if not, `pip install cairo-lang` , preferably in a python virtual environment), you can do that in python:
```
from starkware.crypto.signature.signature import (
    private_to_stark_key, get_random_private_key)
private_key = get_random_private_key()
public_key = private_to_stark_key(private_key)
print(f'Private key: {private_key}')
print(f'Public key: {public_key}')
```

Author: giraeffleaeffle
Content: Hi, is there a limit of transactions that you can put in a proof? How often are the proofs done? You wrote in a post that you minted 600k NFTs in one STARK proof. How do you get to the 9000 tx/s?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Ethereum these days supports about 30Mgas per block every 15 seconds. A typical proof costs roughly 5Mgas. So, today Ethereum could theoretically handle one proof every 2.5 seconds. For a proof of 600K txs that implies 240K txs/sec (!).
However, not all txs are equal: mint transactions are cheaper than transfers which are cheaper than exchanges.

Author: perama
Content:
It's is related to the fact there are two compilers: starknet-compile and cairo-compile

This Cairo program requires cairo-compile. A StarkNet contract may only use hints that are explicitly whitelisted (E.g., some common library modules)

Content:
@Liron I'm running into a similar problem reported by @martriay back in August as I try to go through the quickstart tutorial https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/quickstart.html - following the steps strictly on a M1-chip machine, I am getting
```
Library not loaded: /usr/local/opt/gmp/lib/libgmp.10.dylib
```
when trying to run the compiled program at the last step. Any suggestion on how to fix this? Thanks.

Author: martriay
Content: for the record: I ended up spinning up a docker instance with ubuntu in it

Author: guiltygyoza
Content:
Replying to myself for a working solution for M1-chip machine, the key to which is to install the x86 homebrew and use that to install & link `gmp`
1. Duplicate the terminal app and name it something else e.g. terminal_rosetta; set it to `Open using Rosetta` . Reference: https://medium.com/swlh/run-x86-terminal-apps-like-homebrew-on-your-new-m1-mac-73bdc9b0f343
2. In terminal_rosetta, open a virtual environment running python 3.7
3. Install the x86 homebrew by running `arch -x86_64 /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/master/install.sh)"` . It will get installed in /usr/local/
4. Use the x86 brew to install `gmp` by running `/usr/local/bin/brew install gmp`
5. Use the x86 brew to link `gmp` by running `/usr/local/bin/brew link gmp`
6. Follow the rest of the quickstart tutorial at https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/quickstart.html

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Regarding messages sent to L2, can you show the L1 transaction sending the message?

INVALID_MESSAGE_TO_CONSUME only happens when you call consumel2message before the actual message was sent. You need to make sure that the L2 transaction which sent the message is part of a block that is verified on chain, and additionally that you call consume with the right parameters (I see in the explorer that your contract sent messages so it's probably the second). Can you link to the L1  transaction producing the error?

You don't need to call state update, this should be called by the sequencer after a proof was recorded on L1.

Author: j2r5m3
Content:
Hey all,

I'm trying to think of how I would architect a system that could store assets on ipfs/filecoin but be access locked for only those that own the corresponding nft.

I know this would be pretty difficult to  keep a secret that no one could copy in nft metadata some how in ethereum main net..but I'm wondering.

Does this seem doable on starknet?

Author: j2r5m3
Content: Appreciate any advice on where I should look/what kind of reading to do to figure this out.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: interesting problem.

Author: j2r5m3
guthl_starkware
Content: Is the data changing over time?

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: good question. if it's a static asset whose primary value is self-contained then any NFT holder upon accessing and decrypting the secret can store it locally / share it immediately outside the confine of your system. If instead the asset is function of time - a live video stream of my living room for example - the value is with the stream, not with any particular frame. if this is the case, theoretically you can simply change the key to the asset (probably need to re-encrypt &/ re-upload the asset) every time *any* NFT changes hand, and at all times all NFT holders have access to the most recent & only valid key. Am I missing something obvious here?

Author: tmierzwa
Content:
Hi all, when do I find the current L1 `GpsStatementVerifier` and `MemoryPageFactRegistry` addresses?
Looks like the ones that I have were not called for the last 5 days so they probably were upgraded/redeployed?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Right, we deployed a new version of SHARP.
The way to find the contract addresses is:
1. Run `starknet get_contract_addresses --network=alpha` to get `GpsStatementVerifier` (which is currently `0xAB43bA48c9edF4C2C4bB01237348D1D7B28ef168`)
2. Go to Etherscan (Goerli), click on `Contract` > `read as proxy` > `callProxyImplementation` (currently `0xB02D49C4d89f0CeA504C4C93934E7fC66e20A257`) - This will be the current implementation of the SHARP verifier (we should upload the code...)
3. Go to this contract and look in internal transaction for the contracts it's using, you should be able to locate `MemoryPageFactRegistry` by the `LogMemoryPageFactRegular` events (currently, `0xb609Eba1DC0298A984Fa8a34528966E997C5BB13`)

Author: tmierzwa
Content: Perfect, thanks!

Content:
Thanks a bunch! 
I also saw that you answered here : https://discord.com/channels/793094838509764618/853954510515208192/887273997820104755

that there was no `inheritance` but that we could use the `import` mechanism. I'm trying to use the import mechanism right now but I have two questions:
1. What's the best practice regarding the usage of `%builtins pedersen` for example. If I have a file `foo.cairo` using stuff from `bar.cairo`, should the `%builtins` be used in the first file or the second file, or both?
2. I'm looking for a way to use a `storage_var` that would be declared in `bar.cairo`. But I'm starting to think that a lib in cairo shouldn't hold any storage_var ?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
1. %builtins directive should be in the main file, which should not be imported by any other file.
2. I don't think there are real "best practices" yet, since Cairo and StarkNet are young :), but in terms of what you can do - you should be able to declare a storage variable in a file and then import it from another file. Another option is to define the storage variables and pass function pointers to the library functions (I think @perama did some example with function pointers). (Warning: function pointers in Cairo are a low-level feature, so dealing with them can be slightly annoying)

Author: roboteddy
Content: I have a contract which is tracking a bunch of state for each account that interacts with it. anyone have thoughts on whether should an `AccountState` struct and a `storage_var` that looks like `func accounts(address : felt) -> (account_state : AccountState)`? Or whether better to use a `storage_var` that looks something like `func accounts(address : felt, account_state_index : felt) -> (res : felt)` ? The latter makes it easy to read/update a specific piece of state for an account. The former would require reading/writing the entire struct whenever you want to change a specific piece of account state. Partly this may come down to how tx fees are metered. (If question is unclear, I can share some example code)

Author: perama
Content: I don't think structs work in storage variables

Author: roboteddy
Content: that would make this an easy decision. the code in the screenshot here compiles OK; haven't tried using it yet though.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Structs in storage variables should work

Author: roboteddy
Content: @Lior Goldberg helpful, thanks. Any thoughts on whether most apps would be better-served by storing entire structs in storage, or by adding an additional dimension to a storage var and indexing? (the struct approach is perhaps more legible, but updating any member would require reading the entire struct, allocating a new one, copying everything over except the member that will change,... Not sure how gas-expensive that will be!)

Author: roboteddy
Content: in theory, as far as I know, no additional calldata needs to be stored on L1 in one case vs. the other, so the gas difference may be minimal...

Author: perama
Content:
Haha I can't believe I missed this. 

Is there a cost advantage to one over the other?

E.g. three felts in 3 separate storage vars

Vs one storage var with a struct with 3 members 

Perhaps if you had a transaction that only touched one felt, it might be cheaper in the former case?

Author: wraitii
Content: (was wondering, somewhat relatedly, about 'compressing' data for storage?)

Author: perama
Content: Haha you beat me to it

Author: perama
Content: Binary encoding of data into a single felt is a good method because it takes some computation, but that is cheaper than storage

Author: wraitii

Author: perama
Content:
I haven't made a generalised version, but here is an example of some data I packed into 4-bit sections for storage:

https://github.com/dopedao/RYO/blob/main/contracts/UserRegistry.cairo#L162

You can use a combination of the `pow` and `bitwise_and` to create a mask at a certain index along the felt. So for 4 bits, each felt can store ~60 values

Author: perama
Content: That handles the `read()`. The packing to prepare for the write is done before loading them into the contract. If you generate the numbers in the contract, you can store them by creating the mask and then using `bitwise_or`. If you have an array of numbers you can loop over the array, incrementing the index by n-bits, then apply the mask and `bitwise_or` to aggregate the new values to the "storage felt". Then save the felt at the end.

Author: perama
Content: The `call_contract()` function is likely the culprit. The program has lost the pointer between the lines mentioned in the error program. So if you have the pointer and then you zip off to another function that doesn't have that pointer as an implicit argument, it is not handled-and-returned. So you can either add it to the `call_contract()`, or you can declare a local variable `local storage_ptr : Storage* = storage_ptr` just before the `call_contract()`. That will make it available upon return from `call_contract()`.

Author: realqw

Author: realqw
Content:
```Today, you need to implement the entire business logic of verifying whether a solution to the puzzle is correct in Solidity ‚Äì that‚Äôs an expensive computation to perform on-chain. Instead, you can write this logic in Cairo, and execute it off-chain. The Cairo program will check the solution and will then trigger the SHARP to generate a proof, verify it on-chain and write a fact ‚Äì a stamp of approval that this solution was the right one. The Sudoku‚Äôs smart contract checks that this fact exists, and pays the prize to the winner. We saved both the expensive computation of solution verification and the transmission of the Soduko‚Äôs solution on-chain
```

Author: realqw
Content: This is the example given here https://www.cairo-lang.org/cairo-for-blockchain-developers/

Author: realqw
Content: One question I have is, how does the smart contract know what fact to check?

Author: realqw
Content:
Does the winner have to call the smart contract with the fact they want it to check?
Since the Fact is a hash, how does the smart contract know that the fact showing someone solved the puzzle is referring to the account that called the contract?

Author: realqw
Content: Does the sudoku smart contract have to compute the hash from inputs? `keccak(program hash, output hash)` where the program outputs contain the winner account address?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Roughly, SHARP uses a single Cairo program that loads different programs from the memory and executes them one by one. For every such program, it outputs a pair (hash_i, output_i) where hash_i is the hash of the bytecode and output_i is the output of the i'th program. Denote this program by P. Now, suppose that I want to prove that I solved a puzzle, let Q denote the puzzle program which takes as input a solution and verifies it. Now, if I see a proof for "P executed correctly with output ..., (hash_Q, output_Q), ..." then I can be sure Q executed correctly with output O_Q (which can be the user who sent the solution). The L1 contract writes a fact for each such program, so by knowing the program Q I can recognize a corresponding fact on chain (tell me what output you claim to be getting, and I'll construct the fact).

and test:

import pytest

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Does anyone know a trick for computing `x == 0 && y == 1`? `x` and `y` are each guaranteed to be either `0` or `1`, and I want the result of the expression be a `0` or `1`. right now I'm using an `if` statement, but that has the side effect of losing track of ap and revoking stuff...

If I want `x == 0 || y == 0` I use `x * y`. If I want `x == 1 || y == 1` I use `(x - 1) * (y - 1)`. if I want `x == 0 && y == 0` I use `assert (x + y) = 0` wondering if there's another clever trick for the above case

Author: roboteddy
Content: maybe `bitwise_xor(x, y) * y` would do it, actually. not sure how expensive `bitwise_xor` is though

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: `is_zero(x) * y` or `is_zero(x) * is_not_zero(y)`

Author: roboteddy
Content: oh of course, that's simpler

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: where is_zero is the inverse of is_not_zero

Author: roboteddy
Content: I guess there's no library functions that I know of for `is_zero` or for inverse, but could use `is_le` to compute it I suppose.

Author: roboteddy
Content: right, I suppose what I really want is an efficient "not" which doesn't lose ap

Author: guiltygyoza
guiltygyoza
Content: it's pretty handy

Author: roboteddy
Content: I guess `if` will cause `ap` to lose itself, though üò¶ maybe I just need to get over it and use locals to avoid revoked refs üôÇ I just don't like the extra line noise

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: yeah before calling is_zero / is_not_zero I always save what's needed to locals so I can use them later

Author: roboteddy
Content: hmmm can you apply the `@view` and `@external` decorators to functions which aren't defined in the main cairo contract? (but rather are imported)

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
If you want to avoid ap tracking problems, you can advance ap explicitly in the `else` part of the `if`. This is not ideal, as you'll need to find out by how much you need to advance it, but it can solve the problem.
As to the specific question, if x and y are already guaranteed to be 0 or 1 then `(1 - x) + y = 2` (`y - x = 1`) should do the trick.

Author: cecco_
Content:
A reminder that we're discussing how projects should name their external functions on StarkNet https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/discussions/34

So far the choices are:

`snake_case`:
* consistent with Cairo standard library

`camelCase`:
* consistent with Solidity (projects that are on multiple chains can integrate more easily)

Author: cecco_
Content: In my comment (https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/discussions/34#discussioncomment-1541234) I explain why I voted for camel case:  a lot of existing react components use hooks similar to what I show to fetch data from the chain. If we have the same casing as L1 only the lowest levels (e.g. ethers.js) need to know how to interact with StarkNet and user code doesn't need to be updated.

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: Also I just realise but your understanding of the way the state is managed is wrong. Roughly (a bit more complexe in fact) The merkle path are log(M)+log(K), M number of contracts on StarkNet, K number of used slots in the contract

Content: We use Merkle Patricia tree to maintain the state. They grow with the number of used storage slots

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Thanks. Helpful. What's the difference in L1 calldata footprint between (A) and (B), as a function of `n`?

(A) ```
_storageA.write(1, 0, randomval1)
_storageA.write(1, 1, randomval2)
# ...
_storageA.write(1, n, randomvaln)
```

(B) ```
account = Account(
    one=randomval1,
    two=randomval2,
    # ...
    n=randomvaln
)
_storageB.write(1, account)
```

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content: This is one option yes. Another one is two have to addresses domains, where one is on-chain data and the other one is off-chain data (or some other DA solution)

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Interesting. I can see advantages of both approaches. In my dapp, it would probably be useful to use highly available expensive state for some things, and cheaper state for other things (same address domain).

But separate address domains would make it impossible for an app which is intended to have 100% onchain state ending up accidentally depending on a different contract that uses off-chain state

Author: roboteddy
Content: Maybe a contract could be immutable branded at its creation as being able to use offchain data or not (a 100% onchain contract could only legally call other 100% onchain contracts). That might prevent such mistakes while allowing for a single address domain

Content: let me encourage you to do so if it's currently being debated

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: StarkNet will have a JSON RPC interface, which should be similar to web3 in many aspects. I'm not sure whether it'll be fully compatible to web3.

Author: kayagoban#8709
Content: It would be wise to leverage the community of web3 developers by offering a compatible API.  The L2 arena is massively competitive, and using that edge could make or break a protocol.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: I agree in general, making things more similar to Ethereum (web3 included) will allow easier migrations. (I don't think the last part is true, though... There are huge differences (e.g., in scale) between the different proposed L2s. Those differences will be the ones that determine the better L2)

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
Hi,
I am not sure where your text is from?
ZK rollups are a fairly new tech, and so is moving currently from "simple" executions (transfers, exchanges) to "complexe" executions (general smart contracts, generalized computation)
This iteration can be seen in Starkware's products. StarkEX is an execution engine for trades (ERC20 / ERC721) and has been live for over a year. StarkNET is a generalized computation network, which will allow arbitrary smart contracts.
So the first claim used to be true but is not anymore

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
So, most other languages compile down to transistor instructions, right?
Cairo compiles down to "arithmetic instructions". It is executed not on transistor but on fancy math equations. This makes it possible to generate proofs of executions, that can be verified later on.
We are working on a transpiler to allow code written in other languages to be compiled to Cairo. But as you probably guessed, we are focusing on Solidity before any other language

Author: perama
Content:
The felt values are 251 bit base10 values 

You can apply arithmetic operations to them or you can treat them like binary numbers and apply a mask to represent information in different sections of the felt

Author: perama
Content:
The new string representation is an ASCII-lookup conversion of two hex characters to one ASCII character `0x68656c6c6f` becomes `h 68 e 65 l 6c l 6c o 6f`. So if you apply addition to that number, you will mess up the encoding unless you deliberately apply a mask and your own lookup table logic (for true concatenation into a single felt, capped at 31 ASCII characters).

(I haven't played with this feature yet, but this is how it appears)

Later a true natural string representation is planned and concatenation 'hello' + 'world' might be possible then

Author: perama
Content:
With the new `@constructor` feature, it looks like the pattern for argument-passing in pytest is as follows:

    
```
# In MyContract.cairo

@constructor
func constructor{
        syscall_ptr : felt*,
        pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*,
        range_check_ptr
    }(
        arg_to_save : felt
    ):
    # Store the the argument passed during deployment.
    saved_arg.write(arg_to_save)
    return ()
end

# In mytest.py
my_contract = await starknet.deploy(
    source="contracts/MyContract.cairo",
    constructor_calldata=[arg_to_save])
```

Author: perama
Content: where `constructor_calldata` is the array of felts passed upon construction

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Asked a question similar to this before, but just want to double-check because I'm writing my whole contract with this in mind so want to be reaaally sure.

```
struct Account:
    member one : felt
    member two : felt
    member three : felt
    # ...
end


@storage_var
func _accountsA() -> (res : Account):
end

@storage_var
func _accountsB(index : felt) -> (res : felt):
end


# Scenario A:
let account = Account(
    one=100,
    two=200,
    three=300,
    ...
)
_accountsA.write(0, account)


# Scenario B:
_accountsB.write(0, 0, 100)
_accountsB.write(0, 1, 200)
_accountsB.write(0, 3, 300)
# ...
```

And the question is: is there any difference between Scenario A and Scenario B in L1 calldata footprint? (If something special happens with structs like e.g. storing a variable-length piece of state instead of a series of separate slot indexes, then the struct version could in principle have less footprint.)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: First, note that your _accountsA is a single storage var, so the write function takes no arguments, and _accountsB is a mapping so the write function takes 2 arguments (key and value). There is no difference between the two cases from an on-chain data perspective, both will add 3 new pairs of (address, value) to the state diff. There is a difference in terms of the addresses, the account in scenario B is spread accross 3 random addresses, while the account in scenario B is actually spread across 3 consecutive addresses (the addresses for structs are computed differently). This means that if you plan to access them together, scenario A makes more sense (in the state update proof, each storage access is accompanied by a Merkle path, if the addresses are close you will basically need one path + a little overhead to access all the elements of the account).

Author: roboteddy
Content: Ah yes thanks, it should've read `_accountsA(id : felt)` and `_accountsB(id : felt, index : felt)`, but you interpreted the question correctly regardless! And thank you for the answer, very helpful.

Author: perama
Content:
The idea I had was that:

The game stores a random number that each player adds some randomness to. 

A user has some input that they could grind to modify the random number, but that this would change their turn action, which hampers the ability to grind the pseudorandom number.

The random number is added to at the start of a players turn and then at multiple other points in the turn they can then draw from the number. Each time a number is drawn, it progresses the generator and saves it.

(Untested, feedback welcome)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
hi! the signature field on Voyager corresponds to the new signature field for a transaction. This field does not imply any particular scheme (thus not hurting abstraction), and is used to pass an array of "signature related" fields. 

The motivation for separating this for the arguments is making the transaction hash independent of the signature. This allows supporting malleable signatures schemes, where you can e.g. take a signed message (m,s) and create a different valid signature on the same message (m,s'). If the signature was part of the hash, then you could create an equivalent transaction with the same hash, which is probably undesirable.

As this field is not mandatory, it will be minimized and only expanded if the user wants to provide it (already on Voyager dev).

Author: perama
Content:
So with the signature being a pointer and a length you can pass something like 

4 r1 s1 r2 s2

Which the account could verify as two ecdsa signatures (native multisig)

Yet at the same time having this available readily to check by the prover who wants to know, for DOS prevention, that a mempool TX is a valid signature from funded account. With the signature being separate they don't risk diving in to a lengthy program with a last minute bad Signature (server cost with no fee paid). 

Although if they don't know the signature scheme... They can't do this. Unless there is a mandatory is_valid_signature() method standard. Or some other DOS protection I am missing

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: That's a good question that we're discussing. One way to go about it is having an "account contract whitelist" that allows the sequencer to take transactions only addressed to certain types of accounts that have reasonable signature schemes. Another naive solution would be a hard-coded limitation on the number of steps per signature verification at the sequencer level (assuming a dedicated "verify" method in the account contract).

Author: perama
Content:
Thanks

You could make a `paygas` syscall function that must be called within a certain number of steps into the program. The `paygas` function could have the funds to pay the gas itself, or it could fetch the gas from some other contract before paygas is called. In this way you could preserve the potential for gasless native meta transactions. 

If the account can check the signature and muster gas within that step-limit, then the prover proceeds with the rest of the program. 

Something like breaking a contract into two halves from the provers perspective:

1. Send transaction with signature
2. Contract checks signature
3. Contract prepares funds for gas (e.g., making an authorised call to some fund-containing contract, potentially with a claim or token exchange)
4. Contract calls `paygas` syscall
5. Prover runs the program up until this point and can, if need, receive the payment even if the rest of the transaction code fails (e.g., failed assertion)
6. Rest of the program is run.

The prover has the guarantee that the second half is compilable, but I guess the contract needs to be broken into two separate programs so that the prover can just run the first half to collect gas in the event that the contract runs into a failed assertion (and cannot be proven). But in order to prevent the prover from only running the first half they need to be coupled somehow... so probably this is a hair-brained scheme.

Author: perama
Content: The account contract checks the signature before calling paygas. If the Sig check reverts then paygas is not reached. That is, the Sig+paygas half of the transaction is not provable

Author: 0xsean
Content:
```
@external
func execute(destination, transaction_data, signature):
    # Check the signature used matches the one stored.
    check_signature(transaction_data, signature) # Q: does this do anything?
    # Increment the transaction counter for safety.
    increase_nonce()
    # Call the specified destination contract.
    call_destination(destination, transaction_data) # Q: I can call_destination without using the Account contract, no signature validation seems to be passed on to the other contract?
    return ()
end
```

Author: Deleted User
Content:
Hey, there is a discrepancy between the OpenZeppelin ERC20 contract and IERC20 contract. The ERC20 function arguments use `Uint256` while the IERC20 ones use `felt`.

If you use the IERC20 interface in a contract, the compiler will throw an error if you don't use a `felt` in the function calls, but the ERC20 contract will throw an error because your calldata is not the correct size if you use `felt` (Uint256 underlying data structure uses 2 felts)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Those values are checked by Cairo instructions! note that if you will not fill q,r correctly, the code will fail. Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
There are two types of exit mechanism - 
1. A general forced transaction which allow any transaction to be forced on the Sequencers by an L1 transaction. This is currently not possible due to the reasons @FeedTheFed | StarkWare mentioned. We might add the ability to do it in the future, though it require a bigger change in the Cairo infrastructure. (Basically, you need to make sure that every function call is provable)
2. An applicative escape mechanism. Those mechanisms are possible even without forcing all transactions from L1. I will write a full description once the Discourse platform will be live.

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content: no, relaying only on L1

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
Not sure I understand - could you please elaborate?
They way I see it - when we have a permissionless sequencers and provers layer, the network can't be taken down by a government action.
In the case of single sequencer (like in the StarkNet Alpha), applicative escape hatch ensures that even in the kind of event (government action), users are able to withdraw their funds to L1. (which was not possible if we only had Forced L1 txs)

Author: aundumla
Content: Applicative escape hatch works by giving sequencer a choice: either you include withdrawal transaction or the application will shut it self down. It makes sense as long as keeping the application alive it is in the interest of the sequencer. I can imagine edge cases where it is not. For example in case of government action against particular application. Permissionless sequencers/provers should solve the problem.

Author: exp.table
Content:
@martriay ngl, code is a bit nastier than yours but added support for Signer if you want to have a look at.
<https://github.com/exp-table/nile>

You need to have a `.env` file like this :

```
PKEY=123456789987654321
OTHER_PKEY=1
```

Obv not production ready since there are a few modifications to make to make it cleaner, but it works. 
A testing workflow :
`nile setup PKEY`
`nile setup OTHER_PKEY`
`nile deploy Ownable <address of account-0> --alias ownable0`
`nile call ownable0 get_owner`
`nile proxy 0 <address of ownable0> transfer_ownership <address of account-1>`
`nile call ownable0 get_owner`

Author: Khachatur#0705
Content:
Hey there folks! I have one question regarding the cairo compiler API endpoint and using starknet JS

So here is the issue: I am compiling cairo contract with this API endpoint: `https://2uuf49xjkk.execute-api.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/prod/cairo` 

Which in return gives me the contract definition, which then I want to deploy to starknet with the default API endpoint which is also used inside the StarknetJS library: 
`https://alpha3.starknet.io/gateway/add_transaction` 

But when I use `deployContract` from StarknetJS is throws an error of invalid program, but when I do manual POST to the above `add_transaction` endpoint it works.

What I assume is that the `/prod/cairo` endpoint returns already Gzipped program, which then `deployContract` gzippes again and later `add_transaction` endpoint fails to `uncompress` the given program. 

I want to understand whether this is better to be solved inside the StarknetJS not to gzip before deploying, but my gut feeling tells me that StarknetJS is sort of "securing" the content which is being deployed. So I assume that possibly the `prod/cairo` endpoint should not the gzipping. Any insight or help is much appreciated üôÇ 

For reference StarknetJS github: https://github.com/seanjameshan/starknet.js
And the gzip part: https://github.com/seanjameshan/starknet.js/blob/5e497126ffac3e5d793da16c426d434dc40b83fb/src/starknet.ts#L237

Content:
Can I have some exemple with account and send_transaction, 
`@external
func deposit{
        syscall_ptr : felt*,
        pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*,
        range_check_ptr
    }(account_id: felt, amount: Uint256, contract_address: felt):
    alloc_locals
    uint256_check(amount)
    local zero: Uint256 = Uint256(0, 0)
    uint256_le(amount, zero)
    # get caller address
    let (caller_address) = get_caller_address()
    # check deposit limit of account
    let (limit: Uint256) = deposit_limit.read()
    # get total of token own by vault
    let (balanceToken: Uint256) = IERC20.balance_of(contract_address=contract_address, user=caller_address)  
    let (comparingValue, _ : Uint256) = uint256_add(amount, balanceToken)
    # compute deposit requirement    
    uint256_le(comparingValue, limit)
    # transfer amount from caller to contract
    IERC20.approve(contract_address=contract_address, spender=account_id, amount=amount)
    IERC20.transfer_from(contract_address=contract_address, sender=account_id, recipient=caller_address, amount=amount)
    # get the shares
    issueShares(amount)
    # mint the share for user
    _mint(caller_address, amount)    
    return()
end`

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
this is the python code for vote generation, unfortuantely it's not in the starkware-libs repo so I'll just throw it here
```
import random
from typing import Tuple

from starkware.crypto.signature.signature import pedersen_hash, private_to_stark_key, sign


def generate_key_pair() -> Tuple[int, int]:
    private_key = random.randrange(1 << 251)
    public_key = private_to_stark_key(private_key)
    return (private_key, public_key)


def sign_voter_registration(
    poll_id: int, voter_public_key: int, owner_private_key: int
) -> Tuple[int, int]:
    r, s = sign(msg_hash=pedersen_hash(poll_id, voter_public_key), priv_key=owner_private_key)
    return (r, s)


def sign_vote(poll_id: int, vote: int, private_key: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:
    r, s = sign(msg_hash=pedersen_hash(poll_id, vote), priv_key=private_key)
    return (r, s)


POLL_ID = 2022


def get_voting_contract_usage_flow():
    owner_private_key, owner_public_key = generate_key_pair()
    voter_private_key, voter_public_key = generate_key_pair()
    reg_r, reg_s = sign_voter_registration(POLL_ID, voter_public_key, owner_private_key)

    vote = 1
    vote_r, vote_s = sign_vote(POLL_ID, vote, voter_private_key)

    print(f"init_poll inputs:\n\t poll_id: {POLL_ID}\n\t public_key: {owner_public_key}")
    print(
        f"register_voter inputs:\n\t poll_id: {POLL_ID}\n\t "
        f"voter_public_key: {voter_public_key}\n\t r: {reg_r}\n\t s: {reg_s}"
    )
    print(
        f"vote inputs:\n\t poll_id: {POLL_ID}\n\t "
        f"voter_public_key: {voter_public_key}\n\t vote: {vote} \n\t r: {vote_r}\n\t s: {vote_s}"
    )
    print(f"get_voting_state inputs:\n\t poll_id: {POLL_ID}")
```

The convention we want to have is an L1<>L2 address registry contract that lives on L2 and accounts can "register" their L1 address there.
OZ have a template to it - https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/contracts/AddressRegistry.cairo
You are welcome to open a topic on it on `community.starknet.io` and set a discussion around it.

Author: ironsoul#6439
Content:
In our understanding, there are currently two ways of interacting with smart contracts on StarkWare. We either proxy our transactions through Account contracts (similar to ArgentAccount) and use `get_caller_address()` in the target contract OR we can pass `r`, `s` signatures along with public key to every function which modifies the state and check signature there. 

Is there any recommended way from the Starkware team? Which approach should we choose for our development?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: I believe the second option will be disabled when Starkware adds fees, and all transactions to  an external method will need to be routed through an Account Contract.

Author: ironsoul#6439
Content: got it, thanks! just curious, why `r`, `s` approach is not suitable for fees? I am not seeing a direct connection here

Author: 0xsean
Content: @ironsoul

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: This is related to the implementation of account abstraction and the security of the system as a whole. In a nutshell, when fees are introduced it becomes very important that the sequencer can check the validity of a transaction without having to execute it (if not you can use that to DOS the system). Doing that is much simpler if you know that all transactions start from the same method (in our case `execute` ).

Author: guthl_starkware
Content:
@martriay I was giving a thought about Permit vs Multicall for approval. It sounds to me that Multicall has multiple disadvantages compared to permit
- it has a small state overhead (one needs to load the approval storage)
- it might be harder for wallets to display (as seen by the Badger attack)
- it requires two calls (approval, revoke) instead of one
Cons:
- Multicall being an important pattern, proper display should be expected from wallets 
@Julien | argent.xyz also

Author: 0xmarcello
Content:
Regarding string manipulation with @Victor Naumik we've built a few helper that might make this feature implementation easier.
We have: 
little -> big endian converter
Utils to chunk bytes into 64bit ints big endian words
For those 64bit words we wrote a few utilities like: shift right/left if needed
Regarding simpler operations like concat u probably need to merge multiple words into an array and then serialize back a string by converting int[] -> bytes -> string
U can fund those utils here: https://github.com/marcellobardus/starknet-l2-storage-verifier/tree/master/contracts/starknet/lib

Author: Deleted User
Content:
Hey, was told to post here as well.

Was wondering how teams can bridge tokens from L1 to StarkNet

https://discord.com/channels/793094838509764618/853954510515208192/917472696361689119

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: need corresponding NFT contract on StarkNet as well as a bridge for that to happen

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: transferring NFT is nothing different from transferring any other messages between L1 and L2

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/l1l2.html

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: after all an NFT is just a (tokenId, owner) tuple

Author: ciphergarden
Content:
thanks for response... i did find this which is very interesting:
https://github.com/mortimr/qasr

but, for example, still not clear to me what address would be returned, if, once the tokenA is sent to the L2 account and ownerOf(tokenA) is called from the mainnet token contract?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: I haven't looked into the code so I can't say for sure, but most likely there's gonna be a contract on L1 that takes custody of all the bridged NFTs. So `ownerOf` on L1 will just return that address, until the NFT is bridged back to L1 of course.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: What I imagine is the L1 bridge contract calling `transferFrom` to take custody, and generate an L1->L2 message by calling `send_message`. Then an L2 tx is executed with that message (which includes token ID and owner address) for the L2 contract to mint the token on L2.

Author: ciphergarden
Content: i see... so for my use-case i would need that a user could sign a message (lets say in browser pop-up like metamask) from the L2 account, where the L2 tokenA is held, confirming their identity **and** that the signer's address also be equal to the return value of ownerOf(tokenA) called from the L1 contract... seems like it's not possible since there actually two token-owner tuples: one on L1 and one on L2....

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: From my understanding you should only need the first part of confirming their identity and not the second part of `ownerOf` equality. I fail to see a reason for the second part actually, if the first part already fulfills the purpose of checking ownership.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: In fact there's no way to "call" an L1 contact from L2 like you would between same-layer contracts (unless you design it to be "asynchronous")

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: Again I don't really see the point of checking the L1 `ownerOf` result if you already proved ownership on L2, but maybe there's something in your biz logic that I dunno so I can't really say much about it

Author: ciphergarden
Content:
thank you again for entertaining my ideas here...

yes. so essentially, in theory, my business logic would be separate from any actual token contracts and be specific to some particular constraints about owning and sending NFTs. This logic lives on L2. But i need to be backward compatible with pre-existing token contracts on L1...
so imagine a user with a variety of tokens on layer1 uses my service: i create a L2 account for them that will conform to my specific business logic and then L2 versions of their tokens are deposited to their L2 account... but lets say one of those tokens is a game item from a pre-existing game on L1. If they want to go use the token in the game but the game doesn't know anything about my L2 logic, how does the user prove to the game's dapp that they own the token in question since presumably the dapp doesn't know how to interact with the L2 account and is checking for ownership of the L1 token; which is sitting in a bridge contract that can't sign a message...

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: Unfortunately in this case the specific game would have to take L2 into account for that to happen. After all, how do you handle L2 token ownership if you're not aware of the existence of L2?

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: Yes you can

Author: ciphergarden
Content:
yes, this is problem i am trying to understand and see if perhaps there are exotic work arounds... for example i read that on xdai you will be able to pass arbitrary messages to any contract on another chain and that it may be possible to control a contract wallet (gnosis safe) from the xdai chain... 
so if, in my example, the bridge contract on L1 that is holding the L1 tokens can actually forward a signed message from L2 then perhaps that would work... but i'm not sure if that is actually possible without account abstraction on L1?

Author: ciphergarden
Content: thank you

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: Have you checked out @Henri-l | StarkWare thread about L2 -> L1 communication?

Author: ciphergarden
Content: no, i don't think so.. do you have link?

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: https://t.co/F4RcI12kuB

Author: ciphergarden
Content: thank you.. will take a look

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: We might have reached the max limit of messages he allowed for this contract

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: But the concept holds

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: Basically, StarkNet has a bridge per token contract and this bridge is passing messages to the contract in the other side.

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: In some sense there is no canonical bridge (except that you want one for ERC20 for fungibility)

Author: ciphergarden
Content: i think i understand... but the starknet contract can be backwards compatible to any preexisting L1 contract? or would the L1 contract need to be designed specifically to be compatible with starknet?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: The thing is the existing L1 contract (an NFT contract in your case) isn't aware of any L2 interactions

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: You can have it as an external contract to the existing contract

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: You can build a wrapper contract around the existing NFT contract, which overrides the `ownerOf` function to take care of L2 login and messages

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: but then your game would need to switch to use this wrapped contract instead

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: If you wanted to mint on L2 then withdraw on L1, yes you would need the L1 contract to be aware. Otherwise, an intermediate contract implementing ERC20 transfer API would be enough

Author: ciphergarden
Content: i see... but then even though this bespoke contract can communicate with L2 it still cannot pass messages to the original L1 token contract i think?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: you cannot

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: you can technically pass messages to it but it won't be able to consume

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: No but it can translate a withdraw message back to a erc transfer

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: We will publish our bridge sometime this week. You will have a very clear example

Author: ciphergarden
Content: i see

Author: ciphergarden
Content: thank you... i will look forward to that

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: to minimize changes to the external application (the game in this case) you can build a L2-aware wrapper contract around the original contract, and have the application use that contract instead

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: but of course the best solution would always be making the application itself L2-aware

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: the said wrapper contract would first check if the NFT in question is in bridge custody, and if yes check ownership records based on L2->L1 messages, and return that instead. otherwise it just does normal L1 owner lookup

Author: ciphergarden
Content:
hmm, interesting... but in my case I would not be the owner/deployer of the L1 token contracts... in other words I would like to be compatible with any arbitrary L1 game contract. or at least as many as possible...
 Or perhaps that is what you intend as well?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content:
well you need to change at least one of the following to make it L2-aware (or at least wrapper-aware)
- original contract
- the application

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: so if you don't have access to any of them unfortunately nothing you can do there

Author: ciphergarden
Content:
yeah, i think you are right...

Author: o1lo01ol1o#9184
Content: Well, you could structure the whole thing like merkle tree:  all that matters is that you provide the last state "block" and hash that matches the bits that are stored on chain.  Then the persisted parts are just the hash of the current state and any queries against that state requests

Author: roboteddy
Content: Right. That prevents the state from being tampered with, but it doesn‚Äôt guarantee that it is available

Author: o1lo01ol1o#9184
Content: yes, you'd need to make sure you didn't actually loose it

Author: roboteddy
Content: If a tx modified the merkle root on chain but did not make available the merkle leaves, then no one can use the contract anymore

Author: o1lo01ol1o#9184
Content: but in terms of computing large, database-like updates it seems feasible

Author: roboteddy
Content: Right. So, ‚Äúnot losing it‚Äù is the hard part when it comes to decentralization ‚Äî how do you guarantee it is available to begin with?

Author: roboteddy
Content: But yep depending on your app and what decentralization guarantees you‚Äôre looking for, this could totally work!

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
@0xmarcello  I see that you're repeating the setup for each test, I'm attaching an example using a testing pattern suggested by francesco (I think, it was some time ago). Should significantly improve things for you
```
gov_contract = os.path.join(
    os.path.dirname(__file__), "Governmental.cairo")
balance_contract = os.path.join(
    os.path.dirname(__file__), "Balance.cairo")

contracts_paths = [gov_contract, balance_contract]

# Need to create a module-scoped event loop, used by async fixtures.
@pytest.fixture(scope='module')
def event_loop():
    return asyncio.new_event_loop()

@pytest.fixture(scope='module')
def contracts():
    return contracts_paths

# Define Protocol to type the factory fixture.
class StarknetFactory(Protocol):
    def __call__(self) -> Tuple[Starknet, StarknetContract]: ...

@pytest.fixture(scope='module')
async def starknet_factory(contracts) -> StarknetFactory:
    starknet = await Starknet.empty()
    gov_contract = await starknet.deploy(source = contracts[0])
    balance_contract = await starknet.deploy(source = contracts[1])
    await balance_contract.initialize().invoke()
    await gov_contract.set_balance_contract_address(address=balance_contract.contract_address).invoke()

    def _f():
        fresh_state = starknet.state.copy()
        gov_contract.state = fresh_state
        balance_contract.state = fresh_state

        return gov_contract, balance_contract

    return _f

@pytest.mark.asyncio
async def test_fund_roads(starknet_factory: StarknetFactory):
    gov_contract, balance_contract = starknet_factory()

    await gov_contract.fund_roads(user=1000,amount=1000).invoke()
    await gov_contract.fund_roads(user=2000,amount=1500).invoke()

    # Check the result of get_balance().
    assert await balance_contract.get_balance(1000).invoke() == (1100,)
```

Author: martriay
Content:
my honest opinion is that EVM compatibility is paramount for adoption. we should not neglect StarkNet (at least currently) lives within the Ethereum ecosystem and my prediction is that even projects outside the ecosystem will need to interface with Ethereum. this is why projects that started without EVM compatibility ended up integrating in the end. To me, it's unavoidable and fighting against it will only slow down adoption


taking that into consideration, I think Uint256 compatibility is paramount. My preferred solution for the problem you're raising, which is a very real problem, is to have a better Uint256 interface at the Cairo language level.

Author: martriay
Content: if we have a better interface (like a native, not a library/struct-based one), there will be no issues in testing, interfacing with EVM contracts, interfacing with frontend apps, cross chain bridges, etc etc. even CairoVM contracts interfacing should be better for the reasons you point out

Author: martriay
Content: I believe Tom's suggestion (a common interface that's smart enough to know when to use one or two felts) is in line with what I'm saying

Author: martriay
Content: put differently, I'd try to avoid "when to use uint256 and when to use felt?" patterns because they're error prone and hard to learn -- and we should be minimizing the learning curve for Cairo development

Author: martriay
Content:
```- Makes code harder to read
- added complexity in testing
- difficulty in starknet to starknet contract compatibility if someone writes using felts vs Uint256```
^ all of this should be fixed by a common interface for integers

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
Hello!
> Short-strings are max 31 chars, so is that the current limitation for messages? 
In StarkNet, everything is represented as an int - or more specifically, a felt (field element). Short strings are the limitation for *strings*, and it is related to the capacity to store data in a felt. A felt max value is 2**251 
However, a message is an array of felts. So you can send larger strings, as long as you slice them to fit into felts, in order to fit them into an array of felts.
I didn't want to spend too much time on this, which is why my system only display a simple string üôÇ 
> Is short-string indeed the correct encoding for strings? 
yes
> Do you expect some standards to be proposed for encoding strings and making these strings visible in dapps/wallets/explorers?
Not that I am aware of at the protocol level; but if your wallet has the code of the contract, he could probably infere the nature of the data to display it correctly.
>  Let me know if you have any resources you can share. If I understand correctly I can  safely store anything up to 251 bits in a felt datatype,  should I feel free to use utf-8 when encoding data in my own project? 
I guess so!

Author: tonysprocket
Content:
Hey everyone, I have a mathematical question. I've been going through the blogposts from 2019 that describe the STARK math. 

I believe I follow it quite well so far up to the point where we create a polynomial like p(x)/product(x - g^i) where p(x) is some linear combination of our constraints and g^i are the unique elements of the multiplicative subgroup with cardinality equal to the length of our trace

I'm wondering when we say that we want to prove that this polynomial has low degree do we mean that the degree is less than the sum of the degrees of our boundary conditions? Or is there some other way to know how low the degree should be? 
In the first example given here https://medium.com/starkware/arithmetization-ii-403c3b3f4355, Boolean Execution Trace, would the degree of that polynomial need to be 0 since there are no boundary constraints?

Author: milan3774
Content:
the docs here (https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_cairo/intro.html#the-primitive-type-field-element-felt) suggest that a `felt` can be negative, but if I have a function that does `return (-1)` in my cairo contract and then call this function in a python test, the value it returns is `3618502788666131213697322783095070105623107215331596699973092056135872020480` or `(2**251+17*2**192+1) - 1`

I have a hunch, but can someone clarify why is that? can we have negative felt values then? is there a way to return a `-1` from a cairo function?

Author: cecco_
Content: Yes I think everyone went through this same confusion. `felt` represent integer numbers between 0 and `P-1`. By convention you can use the numbers between `P/2` and `P` to represent negative numbers since, thanks to modulo arithmetic, it still works. Imagine `P = 7`, then `3 - 2` is really `3 + 5 mod 7` which is `1` as expected.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
I used BigInt3 in the interface only because the internal implementation is using BigInt3. But the interface (and only it) can be modified to use Uint256 instead of BigInt3.
The reason BigInt3 is used in the interface is performance: One felt is not enough to hold a 256-bit integer (it can handle 251 bits). Two felts (like Uint256) will mean each handling 128 bit, so I won't be able to multiply two such numbers without overflowing (because 2*128 > 251). So three üôÇ

Author: roboteddy
Content: try putting `tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr` at the bottom of each part of the if section and the else section (i.e., put that line after `IERC721.transfer_from` and `map_bidder.write(...)`. the reasons why this is necessary are a bit "under the hood" but a full reading of the cairo docs does explain

Author: ltdai010#2127

Author: ltdai010#2127
Content:
`func finish{pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*, syscall_ptr : felt*, range_check_ptr}(
    _contract_sale: felt, _token_id: felt):
    alloc_locals
    let (local auction) = map_auction.read(contract_sale=_contract_sale, token_id=_token_id)
    let (local caller) = get_caller_address()
    let (local this_address) = get_contract_address()
    assert auction.ended = 0
    assert auction.creator = caller
    if auction.highest_bidder == 0:
        IERC721.transfer_from(contract_address=_contract_sale, _from=this_address, to=auction.creator, token_id=_token_id)
        tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr
        tempvar pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin* = pedersen_ptr
    else:
        # transfer erc721 to highest bidder
        IERC721.transfer_from(contract_address=_contract_sale, _from=this_address, to=auction.highest_bidder, token_id=_token_id)
        tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr
        tempvar pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin* = pedersen_ptr
        let (local bidded) = map_bidder.read(contract_sale=_contract_sale, token_id=_token_id, bidder=caller)
        # transfer coins to creator
        IERC20.transferFrom(contract_address=auction.coin_buy, sender=this_address, recipient=auction.creator, amount=bidded)
        tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr
        tempvar pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin* = pedersen_ptr
        # set balance to 0
        map_bidder.write(contract_sale=_contract_sale, token_id=_token_id, bidder=auction.highest_bidder, value=Uint256(0,0))
        tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr
        tempvar pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin* = pedersen_ptr
    end
    auction.ended = 1
    map_auction.write(contract_sale=_contract_sale, token_id=_token_id, value=auction)
    return ()
end`
Thank you, this work for me!

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
good question, it's harder to reason about future finalities while there is only one sequencer, but basically you can imagine something along the lines of:
- some mechanism for a lower degree of finality, e.g. protocol for communicating on l2 and commiting on checkpoints that will be proven later (with some slashing mechanism in the baground, providing the finality)
- communicating with the sequencer to get a trusted, but more immediate result on the state of the system. 

You might be interested in this thread https://community.starknet.io/t/how-long-will-finality-take-on-mainnet/72/2

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: On another topic, I have an argument for using Uint 256 across the board @andrepn#3628.  Cairo can be instantiated on other field (like binary field or 64 bit prime for efficiency). Using felt across the board would make programs Cairo instance dependant. For future proofness, building everything using a higher level abstraction is very useful

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: A small note, calldata is not part of the state update transaction. When this transaction is sent, calldata should have already been sent on a previous transaction. Regarding the actual format, you can see more here https://starknet.io/on-chain-data/. It indeed doesn't contain bytecode, but the code is reflected in the state in the sense that the contract address is derived partly by the bytecode (see contract address/contract hash here https://starknet.io/contracts/)
