Author: peteris.
Content:
Q: How does the `uint256` library work when it uses hints?

The Open Zeppelin `ERC20_base` implementation uses `uint256_add` (https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/contracts/token/ERC20_base.cairo#L6)
In cairo-lang, `uint256_add` is using `%{` (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/cairo/common/uint256.cairo#L36)
The syntax reference says `%{` are hints (https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/reference/syntax.html#hints)
However, the Hello StarkNet tutorial says hints are not available in StarkNet contracts (https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/intro.html#programming-without-hints)

How does it work? Is `uint256_add` meant to be refactored in the future without hints?

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Hints aren‚Äôt available for regular StarkNet users because they create a security vulnerability (executing arbitrary code on the sequencer)

However the standard Cairo lib has some expressly whitelisted hints, including those in the uint256 library.

Author: roboteddy
Content: (Hints can speed up proving and/or simplify implementation, but using them in your own code isn‚Äôt strictly necessary)

Author: cecco_
Content: Does anyone have a good trick to store 2 16-bit words into a felt? I guess not or uint256 could be optimized üôÇ

Author: peteris.
Content: what sort of operations do you need to be able to do on the words (full arithmetic or just storage)? how would you optimize uint256 if you knew this btw?

Author: cecco_
Content: I have data that fits in 16 bits and I want to pack it. I want to pass this data to a function as array, so if I could pack 2 words in one felt it would be sweet. Otherwise I have to either split some way else (3 words in 2 felts?) or waste a lot of space.

Author: peteris.
Content:
This may be very naive since I've just started to learn cairo; lets say you have 2 felts a, b each of them can be represented with only 16 bits (0 <= num < 2^16) . To encode it into a single felt you could do `x = a * 2^16 + b` 

Then `b == bitwise_and(x, (2^16-1))`
And `a == bitwise_and(x, (2^16 * (2^16 - 1))) / 2^16)`

Author: peteris.
Content: Would this work? The idea is to emulate a shift right / shift left using modular division and multiplication. In terms of getting the `or` and `and` operations, I guess you can get them from bitwise library (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/cairo/common/bitwise.cairo)

Author: peteris.
Content: [one has to be careful, the reason the multiplication works is because we won't have overflow and the reason the division works is because we have divisibility - modular division doesn't truncate, so we have to have that `bitwise_and` before we divide]

Author: exp.table
Content: Is it possible to input the result of a  function **F1** (on starknet) in another function with the condition that this input has been produced by **F1**, that could be eventually verified in the second function?

Author: roboteddy
Content: (Not sure if this is helpful, but would it do the trick if you made a contract that did nothing but call F1 and then call your second function, and the second function checked get_caller_address to make sure it was receiving from that contract?)

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Another possibility would be to generate a proof of computational soundness (eg a STARK) offline, eg a proof that ‚ÄúY is the result of F1(x)‚Äù where F1 is some function on StarkNet, and then to pass that proof into the second function where it is verified.

It would be a bunch of work to generate the proof though, and you‚Äôd need to be able to verify a stark within Cairo which is I believe on the roadmap but not here yet.

Author: roboteddy
Content: If you‚Äôre up for explaining what you‚Äôre trying to achieve, there might be another route to get there

Author: exp.table
roboteddy
Content: I'm probably still missing something, but: Is there a reason e.g. `let (f1_out) = F1(initial_state, other_input)` followed immediately by `F2(f1_out)` wouldn't work? as long as `F2` isn't marked `@view` or `@external` it won't be invokable externally ‚Äî i.e., as long as the contract code you write only ever calls `F2` with the output of `F1`, you'd have the guarantee you're asking for

Author: exp.table
Content: Yeah, but depending on the application you have, it could easily be hundreds if not thousands storage writes, while if you can just do one write at the end, it would be so much more efficient

Author: exp.table
Content: Not even accounting for rate-limiting issues with the endpoint

Author: roboteddy
Content: I think I'm still missing context, but in theory if you write to the same storage vars a thousand times within a single batch (~1-2 hrs?) you'll still only pay for a single write. (I'm not sure if the starknet v0 pricing scheme will reflect this, but I imagine it ultimately well)

Author: roboteddy
Content: (maybe you're saying that your application's local client might make a bazillion updates, and you don't want to share all those intermediary updates in transactions at all, but rather to just push forward a final update, while maintaining an assurance that the client behaved correctly?) Anyway happy to engage further with helpful if given more context, no pressure though!

Author: roboteddy
Content: does `F1` take any arguments that change, other than the prior state? If not might, be able to call `F1` in a loop in a single cairo transaction. If you really are dealing with thousands of updates per second per user, though, you might be operating beyond what's feasible for proofs of computational integrity at the moment. In that case you could switch to some kind of bonded system, whereby a validator asserts the output, and anyone can challenge it. in the event of a challenge, the all the computation is actually run on-chain to figure out who was right. (this would be kind of like embedding a mini app-specific optimistic rollup inside of StarkNet)

Author: milan3774
Content: I had a look, very cool! wouldn't it be enough to use `autouse=True` on the ctx_factory fixture instead of build_cache.py?

Author: roboteddy
Content:
thanks! I'm not a pytest expert, but it looks like `autouse=True` just makes it so you don't need to explicitly list a fixture for it to be used ‚Äî I'm not sure I see how this would help. There are two speed-ups:

1. Being able to use `yarn test:build-cache` once, and then run `yarn test:use-cache` multiple times in a row even as you add/modify/debug tests (as long as you're modifying your tests, rather than your cached fixture or cairo code)

2. The fact that `yarn test:use-cache` uses `pytest-xdist` to parallelize execution of tests, where each each test is able to run against a cache that just needed to be built once.

Author: milan3774
Content: it wouldn't be a speed up, you just wouldn't need to have the `test:build-cache` step, granted though it's just a different approach, nothing wrong with either

Author: roboteddy
Content: ah however `test:build-cache` is what clears out the previous cache... otherwise, the cache would just stick around forever!

Author: roboteddy
Content: (a cleaner solution might be to make the cache key depend on the hashes of all the files that the cache depends on. then, the separate command wouldn't be necessary. however even in this case, you'd end up with the cache being rebuilt multiple times when it's dirty and the tests are running in parallel)

Author: tsai#7666
Content: We know that an `ACCEPTED_ON_L1` block is final. What about the `ACCEPTED_ON_L2` blocks, will an `ACCEPTED_ON_L2` block be aborted? Or all `ACCEPTED_ON_L2` will be accepted on `L1` sooner or later.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: In the current version of StarkNet ACCEPTED_ON_L2 will almost surely become ACCEPTED_ON_L1 later (on mainnet it can take a few hours, but it'll probably be shorter in StarkNet Universe). The only case where ACCEPTED_ON_L2 will become aborted is where something bad happened, for example, the block contained handling of an L1 message that disappeared due to a reorg in L1. Since StarkNet is waiting for a few confirmations on L1 regarding L1->L2 messages this is not very likely, but it should give you an idea on the things that can go wrong

Author: tsai#7666
Content: Does it mean even ACCEPTED_ON_L1 could be aborted (though rare) due to a reorg in L1? Or ACCEPTED_ON_L1 is generally considered final (with enough confirmations).

Content: L1 reorgs can always change anything right? we can only be as secure as Etherum, not more.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: I don't have exact intervals, but you should be able to see it much sooner than the next L1 verification by querying the pending block. An l1_handler activation is just like any other transaction (the only difference is in the sequencer backend, when is it taking incoming txs and when is it checking for messages sent from l1). As such, it will be added to the new block, and from that moment on you should be able to see it by querying the API with blockNumer=pending.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Not exactly, for a block you do have PENDING / ACCEPTED_ON_L2 / ACCEPTED_ON_L1 but not received/ not received (those only exist for transactions). Unique statuses for a block are ABORTED / REVERTED, where the former means that the block creation failed somewhere on L2, and the latter implies rejection on L1.

Author: arckrai
Content: Thanks for the info so far @FeedTheFed | StarkWare @Jonathan LEI. I was wondering if there is a way to calculate the average L1 gas usage/footprint for a transaction (so for a batch of transactions processed on starknet, what is the cost to post data to L1). Is there any transactions/calls where I could do something like grab the number of transactions processed in a batch, get the gasUsed to post that batch to L1 and figure out the average gas by doing total_transactions/cumulative_gas_used? Cheers

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Depends what exactly your interested in.

If you care about calldata costs, then roughly every cell update is 1k gas (you post the storage address and the new value, each 32 byte which is 512 gas since 1 byte = 16 gas). In the coming days we will publish a formula for fee calculation, which reflects the l1 signature (coming from storage updates and messages), and in the coming weeks we will have an api for estimating the fee (in the alpha version) for a given transaction.

If you want some aggregates, then I can suggest executing the above code to obtain the amount of calldata, and using the get_block api to see how many transactions were included (transaction receipts which appear on get block also return the # of steps, so you would be able to factor in l2 costs as well, once the formula is published).

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: There's an ongoing effort, lead by @0xmarcello, to implement l1 storage proofs in starknet. Basically, you would prove that in block x address `a` contained value `v`. However, I'm not sure that you need the full power of storage proofs. You can send the nft data as parameters to a starknet tx, compute the winner and the keccak of the input (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-examples/blob/master/keccak/keccak.cairo note that this is not optimized as can be and I think limited to 128 bytes). Then you could just send the keccak and the winner id as a message to l1. The tradeoff here is between the cost of Ethereum calldata (involved in sending a message) and keccak computations on l2.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: It mentioned: Synchronous calls from L2 to L1 become possible with ZKRollups ‚Äî could you elaborate a bit?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
In the previous Eth2 sharding proposal you have the beacon chain + N shards. The timeline is devided into slots, in each slot a shard block can be proposed for every shard. Each shard has a comitte of validators, responssible for voting on accepting the block if the data corresponding to its header is available to the network (it does so by randomly sampling parts of the block). The execution environment (where regular EVM txs are sent, IIUC these are beacon blocks) only has access to the headers of the shard blocks. The idea for rollups under this design is to send data to some shard, and have the rollup contract access it only via the header. Since shards blocks are independent from beacon blocks, you will have to wait for the shard data to be included, and track the shard untill the data is there. Only then you can call your rollup contract and say "look at the header of block x in shard y, make sure that the data corresponding to this header is indeed to one expected to be published".

In the new design, there is only one global comittee rather than per shard, and the shard blocks are accepted alongside beacon blocks. This means that a tx would have regular calldata + data blob for a shard. In this simpler design you could send that data alongside the the rollup state update, saving you the need to look in past shard blocks (this is the l1-l2 synchronicity mentioned there). Note that the benefit to the rollup is not immediate, e.g. we send the calldata prior to state updates as part of our architecture, though if you imagine a bigger change involving utilizing shards this may be useful.

Author: peteris.
Content:
have no idea how close you would get but there are 2 techniques that would probably be key here:

- one is a form of functional reactive programming => you should ensure that each object's movement is predictable between 2 transactions (e.g., Dark Forest). Nice paper here: http://conal.net/papers/plilpalp98/
- another is to use client-side interpolation https://dignitas.gg/articles/blogs/CSGO/9512/tickrate-interpolation-lag-compensation-and-you-probably-not-the-reason-why-you-just-missed-that-shot

you could interpolate at any framerate you like but everything needs to be perfectly predicated on things changing in transactions

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: we will soon add the transaction's lifecycle to the technical documentation in starknet.io, but the TLDR is that our backend receives the transaction (status RECEIVED), it is then ran localy and upon successful execution added to the current block under construction (status PENDING). Once the l2 block is closed it moves to status ACCEPTED_ON_L2, at this time the block its included in is passed to the proving service. Once the proof was accepted on-chain, a state update transaction is sent to the L1 contract, finalizing the block, at which point the transaction is ACCEPTED_ON_L1.

Content: Thx and one more question, I don't get what exactly virtual column is and why virtual column is needed. So hard to understand chapter 9

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Chapter 9 is rather technical, yes. A virtual column is just a set of cells representing some role. For example, if I have a repeating constraint that says x_i is non zero, we can introduce a new "virtual column" of y_i's with the additional constraints x_i*y_i=1.

The simpler example for a computation trace is a Turing machine running in space-time (T,S). We can represent its computation as a T*S table, where rows are steps and columns are tape cells. In this example, the role of the columns is clear. In our case, we have many cells with different roles (there are the registers pc/ap/fp), memory cells, and auxiliary variables used for expressing the constraints more easily (e.g. the y_i's in the above example). Having a full row for each computation step (as in the TM trace example) is too expensive, resulting in a huge waste. This is why cells are divided into semantic roles and are spread across the table in a way that attempts to minimize the size of the table and avoid unused cells.

Content:
Hi, I'm trying to fix revoked refs in this file https://github.com/marcellobardus/starknet-l2-storage-verifier/blob/master/contracts/starknet/FactsRegistry.cairo I've also tried tempvars and rebinding implicit args but none of those worked. Any suggestions?
The compiler error is:
```bitset.cairo:7:19: Reference 'range_check_ptr' was revoked.
E               func bitset4_get{ range_check_ptr }(bitset: felt, position: felt) -> (res: felt):```

```FactsRegistry.cairo:147:34: While trying to retrieve the implicit argument 'range_check_ptr' in:
E                   let (local save_code_hash) = bitset4_get(options_set, 2)```

Author: roboteddy
Content: can you paste the error message you're getting? maybe this channel can help you solve a specific error and then you can extend the solution throughout your code

Author: 0xmarcello
Content: sure, i just attached the compiler error

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
yeah the issue is the if right before the call
in one branch you may change range_check_ptr (write to a storage variable makes use of a range check and thus increases the pointer) and in the other you do nothing, so during compilation we don't know where range_check_ptr is in the next line. You would have to fix this for syscall_ptr and pedersen_ptr as well.
 
Add an else clause, and add the line `tempvar range_check_ptr=range_check_ptr` in the end of the if branch and in the end of the else branch. This way, independently of the branch chosen, range_check_ptr is a reference to [ap].

Author: iondex#9997
Content: Hello! I'm trying to understand the internals of the Cairo and its VirtualMachine. I noticed that Cairo uses 'hints' for non-deterministic calculation. However, in the context of the blockchain, how does the prover obtain the information of the hints?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: They can be part of the contract source code (not actually the bytecode that's eventually executed, think of them as similar to comments). In a distributed setting this can cause problems, e.g. you can deploy a contract and specifiy a hint that takes several hours to run and eventually is not even the right hint required for the proof. To avoid such scenarios, in StarkNet hints (which are basically python code) are whitelisted in the protocol level.

Author: iondex#9997
Content: Like syscalls that specify different 'selector's?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Not sure what do you mean exactly, but syscalls are an example of nondeterminism in StarkNet. When you initiate a syscall, the response is just taken from a hint (see syscalls.cairo) and eventually all those responses are verified to be correct.

Author: iondex#9997
Content: So there must be some content in the bytecode that actually 'represents' the syscall, is that correct? Any way what I want to ask is how does 'hints' present in the blockchain context, if not in the generated bytecode.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: If the sequencer knows the source code, the hints appear there. It doesn't have to be part of the generated bytecode to exist in a blockchain context (same as bytecode itself is not part of the world state in Ethereum, only its hash, but obviously full nodes must store it to execute code)

Author: iondex#9997
Content: So there is a trade-off: if I'm using some 'non-standard' custom hints in my source code, I HAVE TO upload my source code somewhere; conversely I can keep my contract close-source if I only use the set of 'standard' hints?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: In StarkNet there are no custom hints, you can only use whitelisted hints, but in general yes. You can't really keep your contract "closed-sourced" if you expect sequencers to execute it.

Author: iondex#9997
Content: Got it. Thanks for your patience. Can you provide a complete list / reference for the 'whitelisted hints'?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: You can look here https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/starknet/security/whitelists/latest.json, but they appear out of context. In practice hints are made available through the use of library functions, take this one for example https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/fc97bdd8322a7df043c87c371634b26c15ed6cee/src/starkware/cairo/common/math.cairo#L240. You should find the hints used there in latest.json, so from the developer's perspective, he's just calling a library function. Behind the scenes the sequencer will execute hints.

Author: iondex#9997
Content: Understood. Thanks for your information.

Author: roboteddy
Content: (Not sure precisely what you mean by multiple keys ‚Äî are you asking whether you can have a compound key where two or more felts are used as the key? If so yes)

Author: roboteddy
Content: great! and btw no matter how many keys you use, you don't pay extra L1 calldata for the write. Basically all the keys get hashed, e.g. the "real" key ends up being something like`H(key1, H(key2, H(key3)))`.

Author: roboteddy
Content: so `_storage.write(1, 100, 4, 123456)` costs the same as `_storage2.write(1,123456)` when it comes to calldata cost. but note that there's no way to loop over the keys in a storage var or anything like that, so you can't cram a bunch of free data in there or something üôÇ

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
Hello hello
I am not sure I understand your question so let me know if you need more info üôÇ
You can deposit ERC20 assets in StarkNet in one of 2 ways:
- You use the StarkNet canonical bridge
- You use a dedicated/ custom bridge 
In both cases, what is used is the l1/l2 messaging bridge https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/l1l2.html
In the first case, we implemented a L1 smart contract that holds the deposited funds; and that credits the funds on L2 once he receives something. It can do the opposite leg of the way, too
In the second case, this implementation is left to whoever wants to do it! Maker is doing their own bridge for DAI. You can implement yours too üôÇ . In this case, the L1 assets can be held by any kind of SC(s) you'd like
One of the interesting rabbit hole this opens is defi pooling. You could have, for example, a USDC bridge to StarkNet, that deposits the USDCs in AAVE on L1 while they are on L2; and simply emits aUSDC IOUs on StarkNet

Author: unidendefi
Content: Ask yourself right now if you remember the difference between `let`, `tempvar` and `local`. I thought of a cool technique to help. It uses a primary character from each to remember the meaning of each. `let` uses E, for expression, since the expression is just reused. `tempvar` uses R for result, since it stores the result of an expression. and `local` uses L, for using the result Later on, even after program jumps. Using this technique, you can hopefully easily remember these differences.

Author: kelemeno
Content:
Hey, I read (parts of) the following article: https://eprint.iacr.org/2012/095.pdf. 
I was intrigued by the Proof-carrying Data (PCD) systems part, and how it might be used to create a consensus mechanism. Do you guys have any pointers, further reading, maybe a company that is working on something like this?

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: Consensus and proof are totally orthogonal

Author: guthl_starkware
Content:
Consensus is all about agreeing on the state of the system (for instance, just agreeing on the merkle root). Proof is about execution. 
Under the modular blockchain framework, you have Consensus, Execution and Data Availability which can be managed independantly

Author: kelemeno
Content: I think I understand that, but here I am not thinking about the modular blockchain framework, but a system in which local consensus is achieved alongside local execution, and is then propagated in the system through further local consensus elements to get global consensus. This would be great, if it is possible to create it, as it would allow nodes to manage their own data.

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: This is still about agreeing on state with succinct execution verification. It is one of the potential direction of zkRollup

Author: kelemeno
Content: Yes, in a sense, but consensus related data can also be included in the local state, so local consensus could also be verified, locally. So this would make proofs and consensus not orthogonal.

Author: Asbj√∏rn#2855
Content:
@odin free | StarkWare Any advice to how proceed in my investigation of gasless native meta transactions?

I want something like this:

1. User sign message that includes tx they would like to do
2. Send message to a gas station (server)
3. gas station checks the validity of the signed message
4. gas station calls a view function of a relayer contract. Check if sender, recipient contract etc is whitelisted for gasstation
5. if yes, perform the tx with the user address as `msg.sender` 

This is not possible today in EVM because the caller will be the relayer contract. EIP-3074 solves this by opening opp for opcodes AUTH and AUTHCALL. OpenGSN try to solve this by implement logic in the contracts to be called.

Author: odinfree
Henri#6408
Content:
Hello @Asbj√∏rn !
Account abstraction on Starknet allows you to do something like this yes.
Transaction sender are never EOAs, but always account contracts.
You could do the following
1. User sign message that includes tx they would like to do
2. Send message to a gas station (server)
3. gas station checks the validity of the signed message
4. gas station calls a view function of a relayer contract. Check if sender, recipient contract etc is whitelisted for gasstation
5. if yes, sends the TX to the relayer contract. msg.sender is now the relayer contract. Given that this contract is the entry point, gas can be paid here.
6. Relayer send the payload to the user's account contract. msg.sender is now the user's smart contract wallet address
7. Transaction is sent to whatever contract is desired

Does that help?

Author: milan3774
Content: feel free to ask here

Author: Asbj√∏rn#2855
Content:
I think so. What happends on 6. and 7. ? Relayer send the payload to the user's account contract and the original tx that the user signed is sent to to whatever contract? 

Important here is that user _can_ have 0 funds to pay gas with

Author: milkytaste
Content: Thanks! I sorted it myself while I waited. Was an array length issue. Good to know for future

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
1. Relayer (server) sends the transaction to his relayer smart contract
2. Relayer smart contract is used to pay for the fee
3. Relayer smart contract sends the user payload (signature + data) to the user's smart contract account
4. User's smart contract account executes the payload

Author: nonamenickname#4172
Content: Hi, where can I find the diffrenet states of a starknet transction ? (e.g. accepted on L1/L2, pending)

Author: odinfree
Content:
The possible statuses are:

NOT_RECEIVED: The transaction has not been received yet (i.e., not written to storage).

RECEIVED: The transaction was received by the sequencer.

PENDING: The transaction passed the validation and entered the pending block.

REJECTED: The transaction failed validation and thus was skipped.

ACCEPTED_ON_L2: The transaction passed the validation and entered an actual created block.

ACCEPTED_ON_L1: The transaction was accepted on-chain.

Author: quentinspaceshard
Content:
Hello evryone, @Iris and I are working on the ERC1155 bridge, our goal is to mint some NFT on L2 and bridge them to l1. Right now we are able to mint an NFT in L2 and send it on l1 like this : ``` @external
func bridge_to_mainnet{syscall_ptr : felt, pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin, range_check_ptr}(
        _l1_token_address : felt, _l2_token_address : felt, _tokens_id_len : felt,
        _tokens_id : felt, _amounts_len : felt, _amounts : felt, _l1_owner : felt):
    alloc_locals
    let (local caller_address : felt) = get_caller_address()
    get_caller_info.write(_l2_token_address)
    # check owner of the ERC1155 to bridge is the caller
    IBridgedERC1155.safe_is_approved(contract_address=_l2_token_address, _from=caller_address) 

    # check this NFT has not been bridged // is not in custody
    let (current_custody_l2) = read_custody_l2(
        l2_token_address=_l2_token_address,
        tokens_id_len=_tokens_id_len,
        tokens_id=_tokens_id,
        amounts_len=_amounts_len,
        amounts=_amounts)
    assert current_custody_l2 = 0 ```

Author: quentinspaceshard
Content:
```# add NFT into custody
    write_custody_l2(
        l2_token_address=_l2_token_address,
        l1_token_address=_l1_token_address,
        tokens_id_len=_tokens_id_len,
        tokens_id=_tokens_id,
        amounts_len=_amounts_len,
        amounts=_amounts)

    let (l1_gateway_address) = l1_gateway.read()

    IBridgedERC1155.delete_token_batch(
        contract_address=_l2_token_address,
        owner=caller_address,
        tokens_id_len=_tokens_id_len,
        tokens_id=_tokens_id,
        amounts_len=_amounts_len,
        amounts=_amounts)

    let payload_size = (4 + (_tokens_id_len * 2))
    let (message_payload : felt*) = alloc()
    assert message_payload[0] = BRIDGE_MODE_WITHDRAW
    assert message_payload[1] = _l1_owner
    assert message_payload[2] = _l1_token_address
    assert message_payload[3] = _l2_token_address

    fill_payload(
        message_payload_len=payload_size,
        message_payload=message_payload,
        tokens_id_len=_tokens_id_len,
        tokens_id=_tokens_id,
        amounts_len=_amounts_len,
        amounts=_amounts,
        index=4)

    send_message_to_l1(
        to_address=l1_gateway_address, payload_size=payload_size, payload=message_payload)

    write_custody_l2(
        l2_token_address=_l2_token_address,
        l1_token_address=0,
        tokens_id_len=_tokens_id_len,
        tokens_id=_tokens_id,
        amounts_len=_amounts_len,
        amounts=_amounts)
    return ()
    # return (payload_size, message_payload)
end```

Author: quentinspaceshard
Content: On L1 we created a function which builds the payload and calls consumeMessageFromL1. Our problem is that we don‚Äôt know what should happen next. At first we thought that we should mint the NFT on L1 by calling a function like _mintBatch() but it doesn‚Äôt make sense to mint NFTs on L2, send them on L1 and pay to mint them on L1 (no more saving gas). So we are wondering how we can manage to send our batch of NFTs minted on L2 to L1 without minting them again on L1. We have implemented Create2 for our solidity contracts so that we can have the address of our L1 contracts without deploying them. If anyone has some advice for us, we would be super grateful thanks !

Author: darkosnightmare
Content: It's going to be unavoidable. Withdrawing a token from L2 to L1 is always going to require a state update on L1 and therefore a gas cost. I think there's a lot of value in providing the option / ability for a L2 user to do so though.

Author: milan3774
Content: I was profiling a slow pytest test suite and noticed that there's a difference between using `call` and `invoke` on a contract function where the former does a full deep copy of the contract's state before executing the function which is a rather expensive operation and often not necessary; up until this point, I was always using `call` to execute a contract's functions, using `invoke` sped up the test suite by about ~25% üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

Author: zelcon#8290
Content: is there any source of randomness available to smart contracts in Cairo/StarkNet?

Author: roboteddy
Content:
Not that I'm aware of. Some options: (a) randomness oracle, (b) implementing something like RANDDAO, (c) using the timestamp syscall as a pseudorandom seed.

Note that relying on the timestamp syscall would require trusting Starkware not to choose a timestamp value which is malicious to your application, and also may not be safe going on into the future once starknet decentralizes and non-starkware sequencers are involved. Also it would only vary per L2 block, not from transaction to transaction. Also, since the resolution is in seconds, it's possible that people could guess what the next block timestamp will be (if there were an L2 block every 2 minutes, then that's only ~120 possible timestamps)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
See https://starknet.io/documentation/starknet-state/
The verifier knows the previous global tree root R, if you read from contract addr x storage addr y then the StarkNet OS (cairo program whose execution is proven on L1) needs to show that storage_root is the leaf corresponding to path x in the tree whose root is R, and that value is the leaf corresponding to path y in the tree whose root is storage_root.

Author: aundumla
Content: That is what I more or less suspect. Can you provide a specific link to the cairo code that verifies leafs against R and storage_root?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Before starting the execution we initialize the following dict https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/64a7f6aed9757d3d8d6c28bd972df73272b0cb0a/src/starkware/starknet/core/os/transactions.cairo#L154

Every read eventually gets here https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/64a7f6aed9757d3d8d6c28bd972df73272b0cb0a/src/starkware/starknet/core/os/transactions.cairo#L345
During the transaction execution, system calls (including storage read/writes) are not verified but are just "collected". After the execution, we loop over the syscalls and start verifying the responses, so at this point in the code, we already know all the storage keys that were read from/written to. 

The global_state_changes is a dictionary where the keys are contract addresses and the values are pointers to StateEntry objects. Each StateEntry entry contains the contract hash and a pointer to the (end of) a dictionary. A single contract's dictionary is appended to in each read/write as seen in the link above (we create a new StateEntry object where the dictionary pointer gets another entry, when we have reads it's just an entry with prev_value=new_value).

Eventually this dict global_changes dict is squashed and we end up with unique keys, and for each unique contract address (with storage changes) we have a dictionary of changes. This is the update per contract
https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/64a7f6aed9757d3d8d6c28bd972df73272b0cb0a/src/starkware/starknet/core/os/state.cairo#L159

There are probably some missing parts in the above description, feel free to ask more

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
This is not very straightforward unfortunately, you have the following rust code fetching state diffs from L1 that you can take inspiration from (this is from the pathfinder repo, aiming to be StarkNet's first full node) https://github.com/eqlabs/pathfinder/blob/2fe6f549a0b8b9923ed7a21cd1a588bc571657d6/crates/pathfinder/resources/fact_retrieval.py
you can also tal at the python script
https://github.com/eqlabs/pathfinder/blob/2fe6f549a0b8b9923ed7a21cd1a588bc571657d6/crates/pathfinder/resources/fact_retrieval.py

Basically from the state update event on the L1 contract you were looking at, you can extract the state update fact. From there you need to go to the GpsVerifier contract and get the memory pages fact, and with this fact get all the associated transactions to the MemoryPagesFactRegistry contract (each tx is one page and contains part of the on chain data)

Author: Saruman#3899
Content: does dydx work on starknet only? and each order on dydx is posted on the starknet blockchain? is cost to post an order very very small on starknet? any range estimate of what cost on starknet is?

Author: odinfree
Content: Hey Saruman, dydx is on StarkEx, the first product of starkware, permissioned, standalone, customizable, scaling engine that runs over Ethereum. Gas is very cheap. A dydx complex tx on L1 ethereum would cost 600‚Äô000 gas per tx, on starkex it costs around 500 Gas. it gets also much cheaper when you increase the batch size and increase the settlement period. you can go up to 5000x cheaper on L2/L3 than on L1. instant finality for the user, the projects takes the settlement risk.

Author: okuyiga
Content: does anyone have experience with using a `storage_var` as an array as described here (https://hackmd.io/@RoboTeddy/BJZFu56wF#You-can-store-arrays) ? I'm trying to figure out how I should implement deletion from an arbitrary point in the middle.

Author: roboteddy
Content: you mean to delete everything past a certain point?

Author: okuyiga
Content: now that I've typed it out I'm not sure my question actually makes a ton of sense. I was viewing it more as a list that is able to dynamically resize, but I think that's the wrong abstraction. In my implementation, I keep track of the `size` of the array in a separate storage variable and then i have functions that iterate over the array from `0` to `size - 1` and compute aggregated statistics.  What i'm trying to accomplish is a way to "delete" something from the middle so that it is not included in future computations done over the entire array.

Author: roboteddy
Content: ah like to delete a single element somewhere in the middle?

Author: okuyiga
Content: yes, shifting everything to the right of the deletion point over seems pretty inefficient (as it will require a lot of slot updates on l1)

Author: roboteddy
Content: yeah, shifting everything would indeed be really expensive. if you wanted you could use a "tombstone" instead ‚Äî some marker that indicates that the element there was deleted or doesn't count for anything anymore

Author: okuyiga
Content: yeah that's what I was thinking as well

Author: roboteddy
Content: and then when you're iterating over the array, you can identify and skip tombstones

Author: okuyiga
Content: maybe have a bit array for keeping track of "empty" indexes

Author: roboteddy
Content: that'd be one way, although it would require ~2n rather than n reads to iterate through

Author: roboteddy
Content: what are you storing in the array ‚Äî structs or felts?

Author: okuyiga
Content: felts

Author: roboteddy
Content: could you legitimately have a negative value in there? if not you could use `-1` or something as a tombstone

Author: okuyiga
Content: no, not realistically

Author: okuyiga
Content: from a cost perspective would there be any reason to reuse the "tombstone"d indexes?

Author: roboteddy
Content: reading/skipping over a tombstone would cost one extra storage read for each iteration through the list, so there would be a cost. whether trying to reuse those indices makes sense or not would depend on the overall usage patterns

Author: okuyiga
Content: that makes sense. In the scenario where there were many "appends" and "deletions" though it probably would make sense to reuse the slots right? because the cost of repeatedly writing to the same index would be amortized across the time it takes to send the batch to L1?

Author: roboteddy
Content: it's not quite clear yet whether we'll get a "refund" for multiple writes to the same cell within a single batch in the first iteration of the fee mechanism

Author: roboteddy
Content: reading is much cheaper than writing in starknet, so it may actually be "surprisingly" worthwhile to just leave the tombstones in place. but it does depend on how the numbers work out ‚Äî if you know the ratio of reads/appends/deletes you could calculate it out

Author: roboteddy
Content: if you wanted to get fancy you could maintain a list of deleted indices, and if it's non-empty when you're doing an insertion you could grab the last index off that list and put the value in that place.  if num_appends > num_deletes over the long run, then that free list would generally be small, and your list generally wouldn't have lots of holes in it. but maintaining that free list isn't free since it costs ya some storage writes

Author: okuyiga
Content: is the goal for multiple writes to the same slot in a batch to eventually be cheaper? I had assumed that the proof just has to show the validity of a state transition, and so a -> c -> b would cost the same as  a -> b as long as they were in the same batch

Author: roboteddy
Content: it's a good question, someone from starkware might know what the early plans are (cc @Tom Brand | StarkWare). if I were speculating ‚Äî only have very low confidence here ‚Äî I'd guess that *per tx* writes to the same slot will probably only pay once, but *per batch* writes to the same slot will pay multiple times at first. (starkware has mentioned prioritizing simplicity over accuracy in the first versions of their fee mechanisms)

Author: okuyiga
Content: got it - I'm just going implement the simpler version of append for now, and think about adding in some complexity to lower cost when I have a better idea of how it might actually work

Author: okuyiga
Content: thanks!

Author: Deleted User
Content: Hi, what mechanism do cairo (starknet) prevent stack-too-deep error? Which occurs in solidity, or there is no such thing as a stack in cairo vm? (Register-based for example)

Author: roboteddy
Content: I think each transaction on starknet has a `step` limit. (A step is a single Cairo instruction being executed)

Author: Deleted User
Content: so there is still some sort of stack too deep when you write a starknet contract?

Author: roboteddy
Content: in effect, I think probably yes. I doubt the limit is specific to the depth of function call frames, but making a really deep stack of function calls would consume steps and eventually put you over the limit

Author: Deleted User
Content: In effect right?, since cairo handles variables assignment differently

Author: Deleted User
Content: Thus being stack-too-deep from referencing a variable shouldn't existed in cairo/ starknet vm

Author: roboteddy
Content: yep. cairo memory is immutable once written to, so the stack never shrinks ‚Äî it can only grow as the program runs. but growing it requires at least a step, so the step limit is an effective limit on the stack size

@view
func get_distance{syscall_ptr : felt*, pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*, range_check_ptr}(
        xmin : felt, ymin : felt, xmax : felt, ymax : felt) -> (distance : felt):
    # Calculate an approximated ineteger distance between two Cartesian coordinates
    #
    #   Parameters:
    #       xmin (felt): value on the x axis of the first point
    #       ymin (felt): value on the y axis of the first point
    #       xmax (felt): value on the x axis of the second point
    #       ymax (felt): value on the y axis of the second point
    #
    #   Returns:
    #       distance (felt): Estimated distance between the two points
    let x_distance = xmax - xmin
    let y_distance = ymax - ymin
    let (distance) = sqrt(x_distance * x_distance + y_distance * y_distance)
    return (distance)
end

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Some communication with L1 is needed, but only a very brief one (e.g. a single message for the entire poll). A key component of the snapshot x project are storage proofs, the ability to show that the storage value of contract `c` in address `addr` at block `n` is `v`.  This is the goal of this project https://github.com/OilerNetwork/starknet-l2-storage-verifier. In high level, once you sent the block header of block `n` from L1 to L2, you can extract the state root and prove (via Merkle paths) any storage in this block.

Author: milan3774
Content:
hey, yes, run time of tests is an issue; one solution is to cache deployments, have a look at @RoboTeddy's work here https://github.com/zorro-project/zorro/blob/main/chain/test/starknet/conftest.py#L167 + the rest of the testing code in the repo

another thing I found to speed up runs is to use `invoke` instead of `call` when calling contract functions - the latter does a deep copy of the contract state, which is expensive (caveat - depending on the use case, sometimes you might want to use `call`, but from personal experience, most often you do actually want `invoke`)

Author: roboteddy
Content: the main reason to use a uint256 rather than a felt is that it supports bigger numbers. if you're only storing numbers smaller than 2^251, then you can use a felt. if you need to store numbers that are even larger and go all the way up to 2^256, you'd use a uint256. (divide these limits by 2 if you're using signed rather than unsigned numbers)

Author: kamadd
Content:
Hi,
I have a question regarding storage access with starknet contract.
First of all, where is the cost of reading and writing from storage coming from?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
storage read - Cairo steps for accessing a specific leaf in a Patricia tree (you can see here https://starknet.io/documentation/starknet-state/ what exactly do you need to access the tree).
storage write - Same as read in terms of computation (eventually patricia_update is called), but the updated value is part of the on chain data, so there's the additional (and probably dominant) L1 cost, see https://starknet.io/documentation/on-chain-data/ to understand what the state-diff that goes on-chain consists of.

More info:
A brief overview of what happens when you call storage read/write syscalls: https://discord.com/channels/793094838509764618/793094838987128844/935474583702745098
StarkNet alpha fee, here you can see how exactly your writes increase the cost:  
https://community.starknet.io/t/fees-in-starknet-alpha/286

Author: roboteddy
Content: `finalize_default_dict` (which calls `squash_dict`) happen within a given tx, so I think the prover would not be able to prove a tx that failed those operations. it's true that proofs aren't verified until they hit L1, and in the mean-time if the sequencer were malicious it could e.g. lie about the current state, etc. I imagine the situation might be improved somewhat once you can run your own node if you want, since then you could verify each tx for yourself rather than having to trust the sequencer between L1 batches.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
The following is a sketchy flow of storage accesses, hopefully this will answer your question:

1. User calls storage read/write in his contract

2. An operation is written into the global dict, under the contract address key (we concatenate to the pointer that appears under global_dict[contract_address]). While applying the system call, there is no verification (this is a common pattern for our system calls), the values are obtained from hints and the Cairo only sees dict updates.

3. After all the execution of the block is done, system calls are verified and the relevant dicts are squashed.  Reads are logs with prev_value = new_value, updates are logs with prev_value != new_value, but at this point, since all operations were done through hints with no verifcation, it is possible that the operations are not consistent. An example would be the following sequence of (key,prev,new) updates: (1,0,1),(2,0,2),(1,1,2),(1,3,3), the last operation is wrong since the previous value of key=1 is 2 at this point. Squashing handles this and verifies consistency. In the context of storage variable, this makes sure that if you update a key to some value, and then read the storage variable, the new read will return the updated value.

4. This squashed dict goes to patricia_update. This will only succeed if for all keys, prev_val matches the value in the patricia_tree whose root we're starting with.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: In testnet you shouldn't think too much about being civic (on mainnet however, until fees are introduced in 0.8.0, on-chain data can be dangerous). That said, currently, on testnet I think the limitation on #steps per block is around 250k (1m on mainnet) so this won't fit into a block.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Precise parameters are still TBD. In the alpha version, all the computation's burden is reflected by the gas_per_step parameter in the fee formula. As we move forward we will publish more precise goals (e.g. "by mid-2022 an ERC20 transfer with on-chain data should be xxx cheaper than Ethereum").

Testnet is highly congested as it is without having 250K steps transactions. Author: mottyl
Content:
Let's do the math together according the SN fee formula.
For the sake of this calculation let's assume you don't have any L2->L1 messages and even you don't change any state (storage) in your transaction (which has relatively very high cost and will push the numbers even higher). Just the 250K steps.
Let's assume the following:
gas_price = 100 gwei
gas_per_step = 0.3 (**Starkware team**, if you have a more accurate estimation, pls correct me)
Eth price = $3K 
So,
100 * 10^(-9) * (250K *0.3) * 3000 = $22.5

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
atm it's ~8 hours for the strongest finality, in the future you can expect two types of improvements
- Some mechanism for a faster lower degree of finality (aka checkpoints). In the coming weeks, we plan to publish a few posts on starknet-shamans about leader election in StarkNet and how it may provide faster finality.
- Improved proof time (e.g. via recursion which will allow you to parallelize things)

Author: jpick713
Content: @DigitalOil.nftr  from my understanding, There is a trade off between gas amortization and L1 finality cause of proof size. if you want faster finality in a batch you need a smaller batch, but that means the 3-5M gas cost over a few txs, so defeats the purpose of the rollup, but when you prove 100K txs, the size grows only logarithmically for gas and better amortization, but takes longer to send proof to L1

Author: tonysprocket
guiltygyoza
Content:
chiming in - the issue above is that the callee contract function `get_total_supply` returns a `Uint256`, but the caller contract incorrectly defines the contract interface where `get_total_supply` returns nothing. In the caller contract, we have 
```
let supply_uint: Uint256 = ITokenContract.get_total_supply(lp_address)
let supply: felt = supply_uint.low
```
The compiler didn't complain about either line; the exception comes later when `supply` is being added with another felt, revealing the fact that `supply` is a relocatable value, not a felt.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content:
additional info: changing the first line to
```
let (local supply_uint: Uint256) = ITokenContract.get_total_supply(lp_address)
```
instantly reveal the contract interface problem. I think one of the lessons here is that deliberate use of `local` is preferable.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Not really. A memory hole is just another memory cell in the trace, but since it is not accessed (accessing memory requires a Cairo step, which we consider the meaningful computation resource), it is even less significant than a single step.

quoting @ilya.lesokhin, memory hols typically occur when you have locals in 'ifs' or early return, e.g.
```
if bad_condtion:
   return()

local value = a + c
```

Author: chqrles
Content:
Hi ! 
I'm developing an app which require to create a starknet account for each new user who sign up. Given that a Starknet account is a contract deployed, I have 2 questions:

- Once fees will be implemented, will I have to pay for each new user who create an account on my app, or account deployment will be free?
- Right after the sign up, if the user wants to interact with my app in a way that require to sign a transaction, I will have to block him until the deployment is complete. How do you see the evolution of the account deployment duration?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
These issues are in discussion, I can offer some thoughts so far. Contract deployment has some additional burden on the network, so it makes sense it will involve a fee. However, there might be workarounds so that this fee is only paid upon the first "actual" transaction. 

Since the contract address is determined (roughly) from the contract hash and constructor arguments, a user with a random public key (or whichever arguments this account constructor expects) can know his SN address before deployment. As such, you can transfer funds to this address before actually deploying the contract (the balance will be written in the relevant ERC20). It can now be possible to allow another party to do the deployment and get compensated from the balance of the contract once it's deployed. Moreover, you can have a tx to your app contract that deploys the account and then (in the same tx) do some operation (so there's no blocking).

This is just an idea (with the fine details not yet polished), feel free to suggest improvements üôÇ Note that the above relies on our ability to deploy contracts from another contract (factory pattern), which SN does not yet have.

Author: chqrles
Content:
Thanks for you detailed answer, The idea of paying the fee only on the first transaction is really interesting.

My issue about the deployment duration doesn't fit any of your solutions. Actually, it's an app where the user can buy an ERC-1155 token after signing up (no problem for this part except that I can't use `safeTransfer` if the account is not deployed yet, but it's not a big deal), and then burn this ERC-1155 to receive some other ERC-1155 tokens. This part is more tricky, cause I need to sign the transaction with the user's account, and since the user is not forced to perform these operations, I can't do it in the same tx.

I'll let you know if I find a solution that suits my problem better than blocking the user until his account is deployed

Author: chqrles
Content: About the fees at deployment wouldn‚Äôt you still be vulnerable to some kind of DDOS if someone deploy a huge quantity of contrats that won't perform any transaction, and then will never pay the cost of these deployments?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: I don't have an interesting estimate yet, though once fees are completely introduced to the system (by 0.8.0 they will be included but not enforced) we could decrease this significantly.

Author: captainlazyeye#8392
Content: Hey really sorry to press on this more but it would be great if you could give any kind of ballpark estimate for what do you mean by significantly. Will help to get a clearer view of what type of applications would be possible. Or if you can clarify if there are any technical limitations that would act as a bottleneck for the sequencer to scale. The sequencer is a blackbox for me so I can't begin to put any kind of estimate. From what I would speculate is that there should be no difference in the sequencer on mainnet and testnet so achieving testnet level block time at the very least is doable as soon as it makes economic sense in terms of ammortized cost. Is that correct? Thanks

Author: ggballas#4060

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Yep, testnet level throughput is achievable without changes in the sequencer. The reason the block time today is much higher is because there are no fees and we bear to cost of computing and verifying the proof/on chain data, once we have fees fully integrated we should have this issue covered. In parallel, we started working on improving our sequencer, there are some low hanging fruits (with some small improvement already incorporated in 0.7.1), but it's still a bit early for concrete estimates on the sequencer front.

Author: StarkNed#7989
Content:
Hi, regarding querying pending block (https://starknet.io/documentation/block-structure-and-hash/#pending_block).
If full nodes will only propagate finalized blocks, how could we monitor pending transactions? 

From documentation:
"Today, StarkNet supports querying the new block before its construction is complete. This feature improves the liveness of the system prior to the decentralization phase, but will probably become obsolete once the system is decentralized, as full nodes will only propagate finalized blocks through the network."

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: In Ethereum there's a way to query the mempool (I'm not sure how standardized is this and if whether all the common nodes have an interface for it, but e.g. Etherscan does show this information), SN sequencers could have something simillar

Author: StarkNed#7989
Content:
Thanks, but I guess here the game is a bit different as once a transaction got into a pending state (out of the mempool), the sequencer must include it (or might I be wrong here?) as well as for every block there will be one sequencer to sign (or again, I might be wrong and they all compete as in Ethereum?).
So what I am basically asking, is whether there will be a way to query pending block and be sure that if a transaction is in a pending state it will be included in the next block?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Seems like what you're after is soft finality and not mempool, and we will have ways to guarantee some degree of finality prior to the proof, but it's hard to discuss without a specific protocol for L2 block production in mind. Soon we will publish a few posts in StarkNet Shamans about the leader election problem and a few suggestions we have in mind.

Author: StarkNed#7989
Content: Great, looking forward üôÇ

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: the part where a transaction goes into pending meaning it must be included is not true I'd say

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: it's just something StarkWare's sequencer does, not something enforced in protocol

Author: StarkNed#7989
Content: That is why they define the "soft finality" and say they will have ways to guarantee some degree of finality prior to the proof (which is, AFAIU, **kind of** equivalent to pending state)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: pending state + gurantess (which as @Jonathan LEI said, today there are none)

Author: aundumla
Content:
Questions about transaction life cycle:
1. If transaction is in "soft-final" status (PENDING, ACCEPTED_ON_L2) can it go back to RECEIVED or PENDING from ACCEPTED_ON_L2?
2. Is REJECTED a final state? In the future, transaction might become provable, and sequencer might want to include it in the block and collect a fee...
3. Are there any extra checks on PENDING->ACCEPTED_ON_L2 transition? Is PENDING->REJECTED transition possible?
4. What happens under the hood when transaction goes RECEIVED->PENDING? Temporary execution trace for current pending block is generated? 
5. Is it possible that proof generation will fail for a closed block?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Intro:
A block may be reverted/aborted, this refers to failure on L1 (reverts) and failure somewhere in L2 correspondingly. A tx can be rejected (the only "bad" status), this status is relative to a block (I'm rejected in a given block, you can see those in get_block queries). This means that if a tx was rejected in a block that was reverted/aborted, it will go back to received status.

1. Yes, due to reorgs on L1 or some failure on the l2 pipeline (no proof for some reason)
2. As tasi mentioned, finality is up to l1 reorgs. A rejected tx is part of the L2 block, and if that block is reverted then our sequencer will try to rerun it
3. I don't think there's something in the normal flow that leads to the pending block failing, so I would say no to the second (up to any unexpected error). Note that it's in an earlier stage in the pipeline though.
4. The sequencer ran the tx successfuly and updated its internal intermediary state, the updates will be applied to the state from the previous block only after the block is finalized.
5.  Should not happen
6. See above

Diagram looks good!

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Forgot that when there is no pending block, the last accepted on l2 block is returned. In Goerli the block rate is much higher so most of the time you won't capture a pending block with txs in it (most of the time).

Author: aundumla
Content: Do you just mean that transactions in rejected block just go to  RECEIVED and can be reincluded?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: yes (there is no rejected block, there's reverted/aborted)

Author: jerryho
Content:
I don't really get the account abstraction(also account as contract) and fees mechanism on starknet.
https://perama-v.github.io/cairo/account-abstraction/
https://community.starknet.io/t/fees-in-starknet-alpha/286/7

I'll try to raise some examples, to see if each of them is right. Please correct me!

1.
Unlike Ethereum, there's no need to sign/init every transactions with your account(from human); Some business logic can be integrated into your account contract thus more can be done, or the dapps flow can be written in a more elegant way.

2. 
But also unlike Ethereum, the account's "not there initially" (available account space, as it's generated by BIP32 it's legal and accepted by cliens/nodes); it has to be deployed onto starknet before it can start signing transactions.

But apparently acts of deploy contracts must pay fees, or we'll have data bloating problems. (correct me especially if this sentence is wrong, please)

Wouldn't this cause a entrance barrier for new users? 

3. (cont'd from 2)
Without EIP 2938, there's issues like when using mixers(tornado cash). one cannot use a fresh new account on ethereum, cause there's 0 eth inside hence no fees can be used to init transactions. This cause entrance barrier. The use of relayers also cause some deanonymization problems.

But for Starkware's account as contract structure, I wonder how the deployment fee will be covered (in the future, not saying they should always be subsidized), in order to solve this problem.

Or I got something wrong fundamentally...

Thanks in advance.

Author: laurip
Content: How expensive, in general terms, is data storage on-chain? If compared to Ethereum, for example. For example storing a million addresses in Ethereum is considered 'really' expensive, but is it also 'really expensive' in Starknet?

Author: orland0x
Content: its about $0.35 per storage slot at current prices compared to about $7 for ethereum. So a lot cheaper but still very expensive to write a million slots! (overview of how write costs are calculated here: https://hackmd.io/@RoboTeddy/BJZFu56wF#Costs-of-particular-kinds-of-writes)

Author: filiplaurentiu
filiplaurentiu
Content:
```
 The return type of storage variables must be a felts-only type (cannot contain pointers).
func array() -> (res : felt*):
                 ^*********^
```

Author: milan3774
Content:
you can emulate an array with a map:

```
@storage_var
func my_array(idx : felt) -> (value : Uint256):
end
```
of course, there's not `length` as timothyyyy mentioned, nor is it dense / continuous

Author: cryptonard
Content: Is there a public RPC endpoint to the StarkNet testnet?

Author: odinfree
Content:
No real rpc endpoint implemented, we have a spec https://github.com/starkware-libs/starknet-specs/blob/master/api/starknet_api_openrpc.json to be implemented by future full node (in progress by the Pathfinder team).

Right now there's the sequencer API, which is unfortunately not documented but essentially supports all the methods from the CLI https://starknet.io/documentation/starknet-cli/  (the relevant URLs appear at the top of the page)

Author: _dsi
Content:
Hmm but then I don't understand why we do  `+ Location.SIZE` in `verify_adjascent(loc0=loc_list, loc1=loc_list + Location.SIZE)` and not `+ 1` to go to the next element
```
func verify_location_list(loc_list: Location*, steps):
    verify_location_valid(loc=loc_list)
    if steps == 0:
        assert loc_list.row = 3
        assert loc_list.column = 3
        return ()
    end

    verify_adjascent(loc0=loc_list, loc1=loc_list + Location.SIZE)

    # Call verify_location_list recursively.
    verify_location_list(loc_list=loc_list + Location.SIZE, steps=steps - 1)

    return ()
end
```

Author: _sam___
Content:
`loc_list+1` would be the index of the second *field* in the first struct of the list. By doing `loc_list+Location.Size` you skip all the fields in the first struct, and are now at the start of the second struct. (If it were just an array of single felts, you're right, you'd just do +1 for the next element)

Is this making sense?

Author: _dsi
Content:
Hey sam_, I'm not sure I understood correctly.

I made this small program: 
```
%builtins output

from starkware.cairo.common.serialize import serialize_word
from starkware.cairo.common.alloc import alloc

struct MyStruct:
    member first_member: felt
    member second_member: felt
end

func main(output_ptr) -> (output_ptr):
    alloc_locals
    local felt_array : felt*
    let (local struct_array : MyStruct*) = alloc()
    assert struct_array[0] = MyStruct(
        first_member=1, 
        second_member=2
    )

    [ap] = struct_array[0].first_member
    [ap] = [output_ptr]; ap++

    [ap] = struct_array[1].second_member
    [ap] = [output_ptr + 1]; ap++
    [ap] = output_ptr + 2; ap++
    ret
end
```

This simply create one struct array, declare some values for it and write them on the output. What I understood from your above statement is that one struct of size=2 in an array will take 2 memory cells in this array. So the first element would be accessible via `struct_array[0].first_member` because it is at index 0, and the second element would be at `struct_array[1].second_member`. It turns out it is not the case and `second_member` is accessible at index 0 as well (like in any programming language i guess).

To go back to my first question, I thought we used `Location.SIZE` to bypass the second struct value and go directly to a new struct. But if a struct of size 2 stored in an array take one memory cell, then we should have to use `loc1=loc_list + Location.SIZE)`  in `verify_adjascent(loc0=loc_list, loc1=loc_list + Location.SIZE)` ?

Author: _dsi
Content: I really hope it's clear, I don't wanna lose any ones time here

Author: _sam___
Content:
Indexing into an array is different from manually moving a pointer. Element index != memory offset (unless one element is one felt). A struct of size 2 will take 1 *array index* but two *felts of memory*.

Bracket notation is indexing into the array.  Where you are doing `struct_array[0]`, that has memory cells A & B. `struct_array[1]` would have the next memory cells C & D. So the offset between the first and second array elements = struct size

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
if you want to assert  A and B and C are true ( = 1) you can do  assert_not_zero(A * B * C)
and if you want to assert A or B or C you can do assert_not_zero(A + B + C)

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: Seconding above; in case you want to branch, not assert, one way is to encode your ‚Äúcomposite‚Äù branch selector. For example, if you have condition1 and condition2 both lying in domain [0,N), you can produce a selector condition1*N + condition2 and decode this selector for branch selection.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: If you conditions are all binary, binary encoding is the most straightforward approach. Consider https://github.com/mir-protocol/plonky2/blob/main/plonky2.pdf section 3.1.1 ‚Äútree based filtering‚Äù for inspiration.

Content:
hey @eddie88 there are two issues here:
- we store addresses without leading zeros so it should be `0x61a872e9e907f557ebd5c788bd6fa3d2ccc77cc0ae944edb21caa02cbda4ffc` not `0x061a872e9e907f557ebd5c788bd6fa3d2ccc77cc0ae944edb21caa02cbda4ffc` I think we should be able to handle both forms, will look into this today
- as stated in the documentation http://starknet.events/redoc if you omit `from_block` parameter it defaults to latest block for performance reasons, so you should add `from_block=106705` (contract deployment) or 0

Author: naps62
Content:
if you're talking about emitted events from a contract, those are only meant for off-chain consumption. there's no pub-sub system in a blockchain

generally, for contract A to trigger something on contract B, you need one of two approaches:
- contract A knows about B and calls something on it (e.g.: check the pattern used by ERC721 and ERC721Receiver)
- contract B needs to be called explicitly when there's something new to read from contract A (e.g.: L1 messages from cairo, that need to be explicitly consumed by some other contract)

FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
are you doing this exercise https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_cairo/program_input.html?highlight=build_dict#exercise ?

If so, I'm not sure what you're trying to do in the above. Think of a DictAccess array as an array of logs, each log documents a read/write operation. For example,(key=1,prev=0,new=0),(key=2,prev=1,new=1),(key=1,prev=0,new=2) represents the dictionary {1: 2, 2: 1}. The idea here is to add another log for each member in the key values list, where prev is the sum for this key so far and new is the new sum. The sums can be maintained in a hint via the comulative_sums pythonic dictionary (why is it safe to obtain these values from a hint? what guarantees that the returned dictionary indeed contains the true result, summing by key?)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
all hints share the same scope, so in build dict you have access to comulative_sums initialized in sum_by_key, the code in the build_dict should be something like:

```
dict.key = list.key
%{
ids.dict.prev_value = comulative_sums[ids.dict.key]
comulative_sums[ids.dict.key] += list.value
%}
dict.new_value = dict.prev_value + list.value
```
think about why it's important for key/new_value to be given a value outside the hint, while prev_value can get its value from a hint

Author: _dsi
Content: So there should be two distinct DictAccess in this exercise ?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: There should be one Cairo dictionary represented as a DictAccess array, sum_by_key should initialize the Cairo dict (an empty array of DictAccess), and build_dict should return the end pointer to this array. At this point you should have pointers to both ends of the array representing the dictionary, and can thus squash it.

Content:
hey, i have been trying to write a simple test (account based) for erc20 using `pytest`, but keeping getting this error `TypeError: '<' not supported between instances of 'tuple' and 'int'`
would be really thankful if anyone could help me out.

relvant bits of code -
test.py
```

        source=ERC20_FILE,
        constructor_calldata=[signer.public_key]

                              to=erc20, 
                              selector_name='mint',
                              calldata=[signer.public_key, to_uint(10**18)])
# to_uint is from the oz utils library
```

erc20.cairo
```
@external
func mint{
        syscall_ptr : felt*, 
        pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*,
        range_check_ptr
    }(recipient: felt, amount: Uint256):
    let (caller: felt) = get_caller_address()
    let (res: felt) = owner.read()
    assert caller = res
    assert_not_zero(caller)
    _mint(recipient, amount)
    return ()
end
```

the contract compiles alright. Thank you!

Author: _sam___
Content: Throw a star in front of your uint like `*to_uint(10**18)`

Author: _sam___
Content:
The reason is that calldata must be an array of felts only. That to_uint function returns a tuple of integers, like `(123, 456)`

The star operator will "unpack" the tuple and turn `[pub_key, *(123, 456)]` into `[pub_key, 123, 456]`

Author: eni7912
Content:
`squashed_dict_end` is a pointer to the end of the dict, and should not be incremented between calls to `verify_and_output_squashed_dict`
+ in order to be verifying each entry you should be asserting `res.key=squashed_dict.key` and not `squashed_dict_end`

So that recursively your pointer to `squashed_dict` will be incremented by one, and when you're done iterating over all entries it will have the same value as `squashed_dict_end`

Author: nic619
Content:
Hi, I have a question regarding the L1->L2 message cancellation mechanism:
If I understand correctly, there should be a way to reset cancellation request time of a message? i.e., resetting `l1ToL2MessageCancellations()[msgHash]`
https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/4e233516f52477ad158bc81a86ec2760471c1b65/src/starkware/starknet/eth/StarknetMessaging.sol#L158-L159

Otherwise for the same `msgHash`, the cancellation only has to be requested and cancelled once and all future cancellation can happens immediately.

It might be used maliciously to cancel other user's or dapp's message by sending-and-cancelling message in advance (perhaps by predicting possible/popular message params `(toAddress, selector, payload, nonce)` etc.

And if the message can be instantly cancelled, it would become an DoS attacking surface.

Author: franalgaba.eth
Content: the L2 contract should validate the origin address to only accept messages from its L1 dapp counterpart and viceversa

Author: nic619
Content: Yeah that's true. Though my point is not about successfully forging a message and trying to fool the counter part contracts but instead abusing the cancellation mechanism to attack user/dapp/sequencer (degrading user experience/sequencer performance).

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
@0xCom @Jonathan LEI 
This is indeed a deliberate breaking change (which we should've mentioned explicitly in the release notes, but missed it). The output of the API changed from int to hex to enable JS libraries to work with the object more smoothly (and the max_fee field was added). We can't do this change in a backward compatible way (unless we add versioning to the API, which is not ideal at this alpha stage of the project), so after all it does mean **libraries should be changed accordingly**.

Note that we still haven't changed the signature field to work with hex, and we plan to do it in 0.8.1 - **so this will be another breaking change**

Sorry for the miscommunication.

Content: Got it. It's clear. Thanks

Author: bobbyt
Content: Hello, I have a question regarding zero knowledge proofs,

Author: bobbyt
Content: How can a ZK-SNARK be a type of Interactive proof, as mentioned in the acronym, it's a 'Non-Interactive' proof?

Author: bobbyt
Content:
```"Approaches to zero-knowledge protocol design, and philosophy of this survey. Argument systems are
typically developed in a two-step process. First, an information-theoretically secure protocol, such as an
IP, multi-prover interactive proof (MIP), or probabilistically checkable proof (PCP), is developed for a
model involving one or more provers that are assumed to behave in some restricted manner (e.g., in a MIP,
the provers are assumed not to send information to each other about the challenges they receive from the
verifier). Second, the information-theoretically secure protocol is combined with cryptography to ‚Äúforce" a (single) prover to behave in the restricted manner, thereby yielding an argument system. This second
step also often endows the resulting argument system with important properties, such as zero-knowledge,
succinctness, and non-interactivity. If the resulting argument satisfies all of these properties, then it is in fact
a zk-SNARK."````pg. 7-8`https://people.cs.georgetown.edu/jthaler/ProofsArgsAndZK.pdf

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
Hi, you either have to deploy an account using:
```ts
const account = await starknet.deployAccount("OpenZeppelin");
```
or use an existing one:
```ts
const account = await starknet.getAccountFromAddress(accountAddress, process.env.PRIVATE_KEY, "OpenZeppelin");
```
then to call a contract with this account you have to do smth like:
```ts
account.invoke(someSmartContract, "function", { arg1: someVal, arg2: someVal })
```
:aPES_BigBrainType:

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content: I got this to work yesterday on M1 and there are actually two versions of Warp. V1 is written in Python and is possible to get working on M1 however you have to install and run some things using `arch -x86_64` prefix. Before I go into details on getting that to work, the Warp team are working of V2 which is written in TypeScript and is a lot simpler to get running on M1. Check out the warp-ts branch in their git repo and look at the readme. From the top of my head it's as simple as installing yarn and solc via brew and running their yarn install script to compile the latest version of Warp. Warp V2 produces a lot nicer transpiled Cairo however it there are still some features that are missing which means your Solidity contract may not transpile. For me it didn't like my use of Byte1 types for example..

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
This video is well worth watching:
https://youtu.be/9zc804NZ0Hs

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content: I'll attempt to post my notes on getting Warp V1 working. This process also applies to getting starknet-devnet working which also relied on Python and the gmp lib. Sometimes Discord will complain of spam when quoting code so fingers crossed...

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
Hmm sorry, I cannot. Spam bot just says 'no spamming'. I'll try and post less detailed instructions

/usr/sbin/softwareupdate --install-rosetta --agree-to-license
arch -x86_64 /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/master/install.sh)"
arch -x86_64 /usr/local/bin/brew install python

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content: NOTE: the full /usr/local/bin/brew path is used as this is the x86 version which is install seperately from the ARM version in /opt/homebrew/bin/brew

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
Looking at my command history...
Clone the warp repo

brew install z3
arch -x86_64 /usr/local/bin/python3 -m venv env ./warp
source ./warp/bin/activate
pip install sol-warp

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
That's it.. warp should work. If you open up another terminal window you have to activate the virtual environment again i.e. run:
arch -x86_64 /usr/local/bin/python3 -m venv env ./warp
source ./warp/bin/activate

Author: franalgaba.eth
Content:
I use this github actions for compiling and testing. In my case I use Poetry for the Python environment management:

`tests.yml`:

```
name: Tests

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  build:

    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2
      - uses: actions/setup-python@v2
        with:
          python-version: 3.8
      - name: Run image
        uses: abatilo/actions-poetry@v2.0.0
        with:
          poetry-version: 1.1.11
      - name: Install dependencies
        run: poetry install
      - name: Test with pytest
        run: poetry run pytest
```

`compile.yml`:

```
name: Compile

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  build:

    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2
      - uses: actions/setup-python@v2
        with:
          python-version: 3.8
      - name: Run image
        uses: abatilo/actions-poetry@v2.0.0
        with:
          poetry-version: 1.1.11
      - name: Install dependencies
        run: poetry install
      - name: Compile with Nile
        run: poetry run nile compile
```

Content: Hi! In this paper https://eprint.iacr.org/2021/582.pdf section 3.3.2 and 3.3.3. - how should one translate 1a) to the rational function if it should hold for x = g^i, i = 30 (mod 32) instead of the given example where i = 0 (mod 32)? Author: anh_minh
Content: Or, what would help me a lot, in OpenZKP implementation of STARKs in the example for signatures (it is two scalar multiplication one after another) https://github.com/0xProject/OpenZKP/blob/master/crypto/stark/examples/group_sig/signature.rs on line 44 the "on_hash_loop_rows" - what is the logic behind the fraction (rational fuction)? I assume that we want the constraints to hold for rows 0-254 and then 256-510, why is this encoded as x^256 - g^[(N-1)*(256)] / x ^ N - 1? I get that the denominator is like "every row" and the numerator should help us get rid of the "ending rows of loops", here it is the rows 255 and 511, but can someone explain this to me in more detail, please? üôÇ
