Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
What happens is that the compiler computes the change in ap according to the order in which the functions are defined.
If foo calls bar, and bar is defined after foo, the conpiler will assume the ap change in bar is unknown during the compilation of foo. This can lead to revoked references after the call to bar.
We will improve this in the future, but for now you can either reverse the order or add local variables to prevent revocation

Author: laurip
Content: The concept of 'owner' is not native in blockchains in general. It's functionality which is added by contracts. OpenZeppelin seems to provide 'ownable': https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/src/openzeppelin/access/ownable.cairo

Content:
why do you think we can't use `!=`? I'm just curious, you might be right, but I've been using it in my code, so I'm wondering if I missed something

`ret` is the assembly version of `return`, I think the difference is that return correctly sets up the stack so that a return value is available to the calling function while if using `ret` you would have to do it manually, but don't take my word for it

Author: soiled#0105
Content: Quick noobie question. Can I write a StarkNet program that queries data from an Ethereum L1 contract?

Author: laurip
Content: Hi, it's a completely valid question! I don't think you can query for data there - all data from L1 to L2 needs to be submitted to a special contract

Author: xjonathanlei
Content:
You have 2 options:
- set up a contract on L1 that does the query, and posts it as an L1-to-L2 message to your L2 contract
- use the L1 storage verifier to do a merkle proof on data submitted from off-chain clients

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: option 2 lets you prove data not accessible from the EVM, specially storage data of other contracts not exposed through external view functions

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Currently the status of events is the following:
- Our regular API doesn't allow filtering over events (they just appear as part of the transaction receipt)
- You can use the service suggested by tokenflow (see the stark-tx channel)
http://starknet.events/redoc
example: http://starknet.events/api/v1/get_events?from_block=145000
- The particular filter in the above is inspired by our definition in the StarkNet json rpc 
https://github.com/starkware-libs/starknet-specs/blob/c3d5ce4499e0ca6c72fc5f70f64dfce1df44de8d/api/starknet_api_openrpc.json#L508
we plan (with tokenflow) to align this with the rpc filter
- Pathfinder are working on adding `getEvents` to the node functionality, so you can filter events that way by running the node

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
As you figured out, the problem is with `@raw_output` which is not supported in the testing framework.
This decorator tells the compiler not to return the felt array as-is without the usual post processing.

Content: If you managed to make it work for your use case by removing this decorator than this sounds like a good temporary solution until this is officially fixed

Author: nedflacosyndiam
Content:
Hello there everyone.   I'm new to the STARKnet / cairo.    I read the papers and theory background on  STARK provers.    I very much would like to develop the capability to construct succinct proofs of the validity of long-running, large-scale calculations that run on MPI clusters and involve hundreds of compute nodes running for days.
Doing a rewrite of the calculation in cairo seems like a non-starter
Many of these calculations are floating point, and converting to fixed point or felts would be a very heavy lift
That's too ambitious so probably it's better to start with something simple

Author: nedflacosyndiam
Content: A great place to start would be an implementation of an iterative optimizer e.g. conj gradient algorithm

Author: nedflacosyndiam
Content: Also very interested in strategies for constructing proofs of signal processing detections - to do this we need to implement FFT in cairo.  This is of course straightforward to do (with fixed point) but I was wondering if there are any shortcuts outside of implementing the numerical algorithm in cairo.   Many of the codes I would like to prove, it is out of the question to reimplement in cairo and felts/fixed-point

Author: nedflacosyndiam
Content: cheers!

Author: nedflacosyndiam
Content: If this topic is too R&D, then I'm very happy to engage over DM

Author: laurip
Content: hmm, a function can return pointers (an array). but when I try to put an array inside a returned struct, I get error `return value must be a felts-only type (cannot contain pointers`. Any idea why?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: @Lior Goldberg

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
An external/view function cannot return pointers, it can only return values (returning a pointer won't make sense since you don't see the user won't be able to see the memory the pointer is pointing to).
When you return a pointer and a length the compiler converts it to return all the values in the array (but at the end only values are returned)

Author: Fu#6986
Content: ok thanks, just wanted to be sure i'm not missing something üôÇ

Author: laurip
Content: ah so this is a compiler trick. thanks. so the trick works **only** if the function returns length and pointer directly (and possible other data), not within a struct?

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: yes

Author: 0xkanekiken
Content: What is the expected timeline for Stark to implement event subscription on a per contract basis?

Author: guthl_starkware
Content:
Currently the status of events is the following:
- Our regular API doesn't allow filtering over events (they just appear as part of the transaction receipt)
- You can use the service suggested by tokenflow (see the stark-tx channel)
http://starknet.events/redoc
example: http://starknet.events/api/v1/get_events?from_block=145000
- The particular filter in the above is inspired by our definition in the StarkNet json rpc 
https://github.com/starkware-libs/starknet-specs/blob/c3d5ce4499e0ca6c72fc5f70f64dfce1df44de8d/api/starknet_api_openrpc.json#L508
we plan (with tokenflow) to align this with the rpc filter
- Pathfinder are working on adding getEvents to the node functionality, so you can filter events that way by running the node

Author: udayj.
Content:
have been exploring the account abstraction model based on this https://community.starknet.io/t/starknet-account-abstraction-model-part-1/781 and the subsequent part 2 - the article mentions that the validation function implemented by an account contract will be limited to some number of steps but couldnt find any exact description of this - in what way is this function limited ? 

For instance, what if we have an account contract that implements IAccount interface as well as IERC721 interface - then we could issue an NFT to the public key initialising the account contract and is_valid_signature could check whether the signing public key is the owner of the said NFT which was minted on initialization. This could turn an account into a more general blockchain primitive where account ownership could be transferred independent of the wallet perhaps - and also transfer of ownership of an account could become as simple as transferring the NFT (transferring ownership could also be accomplished by simply changing the stored public key in the account contract but just trying to understand whether this is feasible). Is this right ? or have I misunderstood this concept (i have asusmed public key and contract address are indistinguishable at a protocol level and this scenario would not hold if thats not so)

Author: jpick713
Content: transfer just automatically uses msg.sender in solidity so caller_address in cairo...if you want to send from another account than the sender, then trasnferFrom is correct one to use...BUT approval amount needs to be set first (one of the nice uses of multi execution should be this exact case, approval and transfer in one fell swoop)

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
If you call transferFrom you have to be approved first by the account you want to transfer the tokens from. Lets say that you have tokens on your account and you want to stake token A them on some contract B the flow will be:
1. You call approve on contract A like that `approve(spender=contract_B, amount=whatever_amount)`
2. then when you call the staking contract to stake the tokens it'll have a line like that `IERC20.transferFrom(contract_address=contract_A, sender=your_address, recipient=contract_B, amount=whatever_amount)`
(transferFrom will check that you approved at least the amount of tokens contract B wants to move)
This is useful because it's the only way for the contract to know that the tokens were really transfered.

Now on Argent X for example when you want to send some tokens to Alice it'll call the `transfer` function like that `transfer(recipient=Alice, amount=whatever_amount)` and the transfer function will get the caller address (yours) and just check that you have enough balance to perform this transfer

calabashsquash
Content:
```
# Write the value of x to [p + 0].
x = [p]
# Write the value of y to [p + 1].
y = [p + 1]
# The builtin enforces that [p + 2] == hash([p + 0], [p + 1]).
z = [p + 2]
```
Why is the syntax for writing `x` to location `p` in memory in this direction? Why not have it like `[p] = x`?

Content: I agree that `[p]=x` is more intuitive, and the compiler will accept it too. The thing is that assignment is just another equality assertion (recall that memory is write-once), so they are equivalent (and in fact translate to the same bytecode).

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Assignment is a more convenient way for us to think about it, but when you think of the program in a prover-verifier context, then even the first appearance of `[p]=x` is just equality assertion. The memory is there (its contents are comitted to by the prover), you interact with it by placing constraints over it. Recall for example that with hints, I can refer to some memory value without ever substituting anything into it, the prover has control over this memory cell.

Author: calabashsquash
Content:
In the context of a code block like
```
%builtins output

func main(output_ptr : felt*) -> (output_ptr : felt*):
    alloc_locals
    local x
    %{ ids.x = program_input['x'] %}
    assert [output_ptr] = x * x
    return (output_ptr=output_ptr + 1)
end
```
What then is the purpose of the `assert` keyword, if `[output_ptr] = x * x` would just be an assertion of equality anyway?

Content:
I understand your concern and it doesn't sound fun. this will mostly get 'fixed' by account contracts requiring a nonce in calldata, as they already do. but, on the other hand, nobody says an account contract has to take in a nonce.
I feel like, without really knowing, that this is a known oddity and is left open on purpose, because the protocol doesn't want to be the one enforcing such restrictions. Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
Hi there, hopefully I'm asking this question in the right channel. I have been experimenting with Starknet and read the docs but I want to check that I have understood the fundamental principals:

- If I deploy my Cairo code as a smart contract, then inputs for the external functions are public i.e. none of the inputs can be set to be secret (This was demonstrated in the starknet-101 exercises by Henri)
- If I want to have private information as part of my system, I'd have to submit my own traces generated using `cairo-sharp` to SHARP (as demonstrated in Cairo playground)
  - SHARP has access to the secret information as it is given the inputs however when it generates the Proof, the Proof DOES NOT contain the secret information (?)
  - The verifier which is a contract on L1 produces and registers a fact without access to the secret information. This means etherscan cannot be used to see what the private information was as the proof didn't contain it. Further to this, the proofs were batched up as a 'train' so extracting the inputs for a particular program is extremely difficult but not impossible
- If I wanted to make a peer to peer dApp that proved something without revealing some secret knowledge I'd have to somehow generate traces in Javascript. I'm unsure if there is a way of doing that yet seeing as `cairo-sharp` is a python program.

So my questions:
- Is there a way to generate and submit a trace entirely in a web frontend without having to implement a server component?
- How do I choose which inputs should be secret? Is that what Cairo hints are for?
  - Looking at how hints work in the documentation, I believe my secret can be in my input.json file and I reference that data from within a hint. Is that input.json data revealed publicly?
- Is there a way of checking if a fact is valid from within a Cairo contract?
- Because I'm submitting my own traces, Voyager cannot be used to see my secret data?

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
Good morning Starknet crew, just pondering these points:

- Is there a way to generate and submit a trace entirely in a web frontend without having to implement a server component?
  - Seems like the cairo-sharp python program is required however I'm not sure if a JS version of this exists at all.
- Is there a way of checking if a fact is valid from within a L2 Cairo contract?
  - So far I've only found a way of calling isValid(fact) directly on the L1 verifier contract. 

I've gone down a rabbit hole with the idea of secret data that is provable. I've seen how this can be done by writing Cairo programs that consume secret data via hints, producing a proof via SHARP and checking the fact registry. To try and incorporate this with L2 contracts has become a little tricky so I also wanted to check if there isn't a simple way of having secret data natively with Starknet L2 contracts?

Author: loeiz
Content:
i have a math question

if we have a `hashN` as:
```
hash1 = hash(message1, message2)
hash2 = hash(hash1, message3)
hash3 = hash(hash2, message4)
...
hashN = hash(hashN-1, messageN+1)
```
assuming messages are cairo felts and hashes are pedersen hashes
and assuming I know all messages except `message1`

to what degree can I predict hashN? Or put it in another way for what N does this system become predictable, assuming the above condition that I know all messages except `message1`?

Author: loeiz
Content: or how can i combine messages that i know except one and get a non predictable result?

Author: laurip
Content: everything related to fees is a bit up in the air still. But there are at least two main approaches to this problem: since the (account) contract address can be precomputed, send assets (to cover for fees) to the address in advance. Or in some fashion pay the fees from another account (unsure how this works, but it's probably possible) - from the wallet's point of view, the wallet provider can then take back the fees from the user's first 'real' transaction

Author: calvinhobbes#6498
Content: Just a little feedback for the starkware team from a dev who has been working to integrate with starknet the last couple of weeks. It's my opinion that a solidity transpiler should be a first class citizen (e.g. starkware should be supporting/developing this with lots of resources). Cairo is a pretty different language than what most devs are used to, and it's hard to see it taking off, especially with the documentation/tutorials being very thin. Thus, making the solidity transpiler a focus would be the best shot of starkware to get more adoption.

Author: laurip
Content:
I think this is very valuable feedback. I agree that Cairo is not the easiest language and its documentation is lacking. Or, I think the language itself is not *very* difficult, but all the tooling around it is still too fresh.
However, I maybe disagree a bit about the Solidity transpiler. Even if there was a transpiler with which you can get 100% accurate Cairo code, it wouldn't be what is needed. StarkNet has quite different capabilities compared to EVM, and reusing the same code in StarkNet doesn't often make sense. For example computation is very cheap in StarkNet. So, to take full advantage of StarkNet, you'd need to either rethink your project architecture or have a different project altogether.
P.S. Just to make sure: I'm not from StarkWare

Author: laurip
Content: (I already asked this earlier with no replies, so I'll rephrase my question). What is a function signature and how/when should it be used? I can't see it in the documentation (https://starknet.io/documentation/starknet-cli/#invoke) but it's in the CLI code (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/starknet/cli/starknet_cli.py). And what is the relationship with `get_tx_info`'s signature data?

Author: calabashsquash
Content:
From a L1 perspective, the function signature is a 4 byte identifier for identifying a specific function (see: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/v0.4.24/units-and-global-variables.html#block-and-transaction-properties).

From my experience so far, it seems like function signatures are much larger than 4bytes in StarkNet though. (see: https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-contracts-starknet/blob/develop/contracts/ArgentAccount.cairo#L30-L36)

> how/when should it be used?
You can use it in any situation where you want to check what function is wanting to be called. For example, the ArgentX account contract checks to see if the user wants to execute one of 4 specific functions - and then does different signature verification depending on which one. See: https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-contracts-starknet/blob/develop/contracts/ArgentAccount.cairo#L203-L204
(There are probably heaps of other use cases too)

> what is the relationship with get_tx_info's signature data?
I think that signature is the one that is signed by the user (i.e. the one that is used by an account contract to validate e.g.: https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-contracts-starknet/blob/develop/contracts/ArgentAccount.cairo#L221-L222 )

LMK if that doesn't answer your question üôÇ

Content:
Ah, I was actually confusing function signatures with transaction signatures. Thanks for clearing this confusion a bit üôÇ

Author: laurip
Content:
Continuing on my signature questions, since missing answers.
`starknet invoke` seems to take in a `--signature` parameter, but it's undocumented. What can it be used for? Does it simply populate the signature info in `get_tx_info()` and does it do something else as well?
Why is this signature stuff a separate entity anyway, why not just provide as regular function parameters when needed?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: It can be used by account contracts to validate the tx. In practice it simply populates tx_info and the validation is left to the account contract. It was separated so it can be handled by the OS and not the account contract which probably simplifies the implementation of account abstraction. I believe the nonce will be handled similarly in the future.

Author: Thomas | BrilliantBlocks#4130
Content:
I have a question regarding the off-chain verification of signatures given an Argent-X account.

Argent-X accounts offer a view function `is_valid_signature()` but calling this always returns a False response for me. Most likely, I just messed up computing the hash.
How do you verify off-chain the validity of a signed message by an account owner?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: You want to verify an ECDSA signature ?

Author: Thomas | BrilliantBlocks#4130
Content:
Tbh, I'm not entirely sure. Does Argent-X use ECDSA signatures?

I try to describe the flow. Maybe this clarifies.

1. Alice fetches a nonce from Bob.
2. Alice signs it using her Argent-X wallet.
3. Alice sends (wallet_address, nonce, signature) to Bob.
4. Bob validates whether the Account with wallet_address has signed the nonce.

The 4. step is the one where I'm stuck.
I highly appreciate your help!

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Tbh honest I don't know the exact reason, but you can imagine the OS rejecting a Tx to an account where no signature is provided.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: With Account Abstraction you should never verify a signature off-chain because there is no guarantee that the key you have locally is still valid. In your example Alice could rotate the key of her account after signing. Only the account knows. So you should always call `is_valid_signature`. But yes, you need to make sure your hash is correct. You should check in our tests how we compute the hash, maybe it will help.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
1. The address of a contract is computed as follows: hash of ["STARKNET_CONTRACT_ADDRESS", deployer_address, salt, contract_hash, constructor_calldata_hash]
2. constructor_calldata_hash is the hash of the arguments of the constructor
3. deployer_address is currently always 0
4. salt is usually chosen randomly when you deploy (so you must know it in order to compute the address)
5. the hash of the list [x1, ..., xn] is h(...h(h(0, x1), x2), ..., xn), n)  (see `compute_hash_on_elements` in python, and `hash_state.cairo` in Cairo)

You can use `starkware/starknet/core/os/contract_address/contract_address.py` to compute it

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
you'd need to use the function `calculate_transaction_hash_common` which is available here: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/2abd303e1808612b724bc1412b2b5babd04bb4e7/src/starkware/starknet/core/os/transaction_hash/transaction_hash.py#L17
The you can use this :
```py
def tx_hash_from_message(
    from_address: str, to_address: int, selector: int, nonce: int, payload: List[int]
) -> str:
    int_hash = calculate_transaction_hash_common(
        tx_hash_prefix=510926345461491391292786,
        version=0,
        contract_address=to_address,
        entry_point_selector=selector,
        calldata=[int(from_address, 16), *payload],
        max_fee=0,
        chain_id=1536727068981429685321,  # StarknetChainId.TESTNET.value
        additional_data=[nonce],
    )
    return hex(int_hash)


print(
    tx_hash_from_message(
        from_address="0x",
        to_address=1,
        selector=1,
        nonce=1,
        payload=[1, 1, 1],
    )
)
```
If you wish to post this question on stackoverflow and link it to me so i can answer there it'd be awsome because i don't think that you're the only one wanting to do that

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
Builtins are significantly more optimized than regular cairo libraries so yes keccak and secp256k1 will be more expensive than pedersen_hash and ECDSA. Maybe @Lior Goldberg has the exact optimization improvement with builtins.
You can read more about buitins here https://eprint.iacr.org/2021/1063.pdf (section 2.8 and section 7)

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: you can use the builtin pedersen_hash which will be less costly but keccak works too

Reproduce:

5. Invoke the exact same function with the exact same arguments.

Author: .smchala
Content: Maybe I didn't explain myself properly, thanks for pointing that I need const, which defo will use, but I am trying to understand the best way to use that const, imagine that constant is used in contract A and also in contract B, shall I declare the same constant in both contracts, or should I create contract C, that will be used in A and B to get to my constant? would the cost (fees) of one or the other solution will be cheaper?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: you can create a file `constants.cairo`  with only `const`  values in it. If you need those constants to be seen by the users then you should probably deploy a contract with only storage vars which would be your constants and create views. The cheapest approach is to use `const`

Author: martriay
Content:
inputs should be explicitly passed as an array, not a file. try with 

```sh
  starknet invoke \
    --address 0x044c2d8ae45bf7e30311eb59ae04b538cd8bc4aa1ce6a982e25b9b84a0f08dae \
    --abi main_abi.json \
    --function get_value \
    --inputs 1234
```

Author: martriay
Content:
that being said, you may want to try using Nile's `invoke`, which is slightly easier:

https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/nile#call-and-invoke

Author: divib#8427
Content:
Hi I want to understand more about how L1 can interacat with L2 (starknet). The tutorial here https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/l1l2.html#messages-from-l1-to-l2 says the followings
> Note that while honest Sequencers automatically consume L1 -> L2 messages, it is not enforced by the protocol (so a Sequencer may choose to skip a message). This should be taken into account when designing the message protocol between the two contracts.

What is the recommendation on handling this lossy message channel? Is it possible for L1 contract to figure out if a message has been delivered to L2 or not? Otherwise, this seems very risky for things like deposits/withdraws, where deposit in L1 does not mean balance increase in L2.

Author: xenoliss
Content:
Hello there ! Still learning about Starknet and Cairo and all that good stuff. I understand that Cairo is a programming language used to build STARK proof and that Starknet is a sort of OS built in Cairo that can execute arbitrary programs and proof their correct execution  (and this is mindblowing tbh).

Previously there was StarkEx with the SHARP that, as far as I understood, allowed people to register arbitrary cairo programs, run them, obtain a proof of the valid execution and then on the L1 smart contracts one could reconstruct the "Fact" and query the Verifier onchain if the fact `isValid`. My first question is: **is StarkEx now (that we have Starknet) obsolete ? **, meaning that as a dApp developer do I have any incentive to use StarkEx instead of StarkNet ?

Now regarding StarkNet, I understand that it is a L2 solution that mostly brings (in addition to all the go STARK stuff that comes with cairo programs) the benefit of being able to have "state" when executing cairo programs (at cost of some features like hints not being available anymore). One can now interact with cairo smart contracts, deployed on Starknet in a similar fashion as what we are use to with other more traditional L2s. My 2nd question is: if I send a tx on starknet targeting my own starknet smart contract, **will it automagically  generate a proof that I can then verify on L1 using the Verifier smart contract ** (in a similar fashion that when using StarkEx) ?

Thanks a lot for the answers üôÇ

Author: laurip
Content:
wasn't fully following the flow, but my guess is that you are executing the `increase_balance` without going through your account contract. In that case the caller address is `0`.
But in general your keypair is used to authenticate you to the account contract. The account contract has a contract address. The account contract calls other contracts, and therefore the caller address is those other contracts is the account contract's address (IF you go through it).
Soon it will not be possible to execute contracts without going through your account contract, but it's still allowed for a little while

Author: bobio9013
Content: Hi, thank you for reply. I've found the issue, I have deployed multiple account contracts, and expect to use my new account 002. but when I deploy this new cairo contract and `increase_balance` it misses parameter `--account=002` So ti defaults to the very first account `__default__` so that is why I saw a different caller_address in tx_trace and get_balance can only get increased balance for old account contract address. as long as I tried everything with `--account=002` it works like a charm!

Author: clacladev
Content:
Hello I have questions about Proxies contract for cairo (https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/docs/Proxies.md). 
1. where the storage vars should live? Proxy contract or implementation/logic contract?
2. if they live in the implementation/logic contract, during an upgrade,  does the storage vars get moved to the new contract?

Author: ametel
Content: storage should be in proxy

Author: clacladev
Content: So it means that I can just upgrade the logic inside the implementation/logic contracts. But I cannot add new storage vars over time. Correct?

Author: ametel
Content: in this scenario yes, only logic is updated

Author: laurip
Content: well storage is in proxy, but storage variables are in the implementation

Author: clacladev
Content:
Can you explain me in laymen terms what it means?
storage_vars in the implementation, but actually stored in the proxy, correct?
Does it mean state remains between upgrades of the implementations?
Does it mean I can add new storage_vars in an upgrade?

Author: laurip
Content:
yes you can add storage vars to the implementation. haven't really read about proxies in starknet, but seems that there won't be storage clashes even if you remove old variables in a new version (unlike in solidity).
and yes, the storage_vars are in the implementation but their data is stored in the proxy (because of delegate calls). state is kept between upgrades as the state is in the proxy

Author: clacladev
Content: that's great! thanks for confirming. I will try to implement something to test all this!

Author: milan3774
Content:
you can keep your folder structure, but you need to modify the import path (CAIRO_PATH) for it to work https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/imports.html#import-search-paths

it should probably be set to sth like `/path/to/your/repo/libs/openzeppelin/src/`

Author: sa.bur.o

Author: _andrew#7540
Content:
Hey everybody,
A critical bug was recently discovered in the OZ Account library. The bug could allow a malicious contract to take ownership of an account that unwittingly interacts with it‚Äîeven if it's behind another contract. The malicious contract could achieve this by using a reentrant call to reutilize the signature and reset the calling account's public key.

The bug has since been fixed. Some important things to note:
- **exploiting this bug on mainnet is not possible due to StarkWare's whitelisting protocol**
- **OZ Contracts for Cairo v0.1.0 release is safe and does not include this bug**
- the reported bug is here with further details on the exploit: https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/issues/344 
- the fix is in this PR: https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/pull/347 

If your project copied the unreleased OZ Account library from `main` *after* #233 was merged (which was late March), please apply the fix üôÇ Thank you!

Author: 0xevolve#5922
Content:
Thanks for the heads up!

Asking there while we're talking of OZ cairo contracts, why do we not have any view function to get the current implementation in the OZ proxy contract ?

Author: _andrew#7540
Content:
My pleasure!

And the view funcs are in the Proxy library for `get_implementation` and `get_admin`. You just have to expose them (with `@view` decorators) in your implementation:
https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/src/openzeppelin/upgrades/library.cairo#L86-L106

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Multiple keys are useful when you want (future) event indexers to allow quick filtering according to a specific key. For example, if you're emitting an ERC20 transafer event, you may want to have the account-from and account-to as keys and the balance as data, since you'll want to allow querying all the events with a specific account-from or with a specific account-to.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Note that as @Lucas | StarkWare said it's not yet supported in the high level syntax and I don't think there are event indexers at the moment (but there will be in the future).

Author: 0xmarcello
Content:
What is the difference between
```
from starkware.cairo.common.cairo_keccak.keccak import keccak_as_words, finalize_keccak
from starkware.cairo.common.alloc import alloc

func hash_finalize{}(input_size_bytes: felt, input: felt*, input_len: felt):
  alloc_locals
  let (local keccak_ptr) = alloc()
local keccak_ptr_start = keccak_ptr

let (local result) = keccak_as_words{keccak_ptr}(input, input_size_bytes)
finalize_keccak(keccak_ptr_start=keccak_ptr_start, keccak_ptr_end=keccak_ptr)

let (local result) = keccak_as_words{keccak_ptr}(input, input_size_bytes)
finalize_keccak(keccak_ptr_start=keccak_ptr_start, keccak_ptr_end=keccak_ptr)

end
```
and

```
from starkware.cairo.common.cairo_keccak.keccak import keccak_as_words, finalize_keccak
from starkware.cairo.common.alloc import alloc

func hash_finalize{}(input_size_bytes: felt, input: felt*, input_len: felt):
  alloc_locals
  let (local keccak_ptr) = alloc()
local keccak_ptr_start = keccak_ptr

let (local result) = keccak_as_words{keccak_ptr}(input, input_size_bytes)

let (local result) = keccak_as_words{keccak_ptr}(input, input_size_bytes)
finalize_keccak(keccak_ptr_start=keccak_ptr_start, keccak_ptr_end=keccak_ptr)

end
```
Why the second costs almost the half in terms of cairo steps?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: because in the first one you call `finalize_keccak` twice and in the seconde one only once. Please use the 2nd one as it's way less expensive

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Once the ETH is on L2 (which is done once using the ETH bridge) you can work with it like any ERC20. So unlike Ethereum where you can send ETH when you call a contract's method, ETH in StarkNet is treated like any ERC20 - the called contract will have to call transfer() after the appropriate allowance was set by the caller.
Note that you only have to use messages to move it between L1 and L2. Once it's on L2, you can work with it without sending L1<->L2 messages (which are very expensive).

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: Not yet, it'll be uploaded with the release. But this is the high-level idea: in 0.9.0 StarkNet will distinguish between a contract class (which is the code of the contract) and a contract instance (which is the state/storage of the contract). You'll be able to **declare** a contract class and then **deploy** an instance of that class. The `deploy()` syscall will get the class hash (which is the identifier of the contract class) and deploys an instance of that contract. It'll then return the address of the newly deployed contract.

Content: Why use Uint256 instead of felt in ERC20 contracts?

Content: because felt is not big enough, it lacks a few bits

Author: swathi2295
Content:
@CalabashSquash AFAIK, You don't need fee to deploy a contract. Could you try this?
``starknet deploy --contract artifacts/Account_compiled.json  --network alpha-goerli``

Author: milan3774
Content: you don't have to actually, I've done an experiment where I switched to felts internally (public API still uses Uint256), it's more efficient this way

Author: laurip
Content: just to bear in mind that, in theory, weird things will happen if the data doesn't fit in the felt

Author: laurip
Content: 99,99% of cases felt is big enough üôÇ

Author: milan3774
Content: yeah, I know, got checks in place, the tx would fail

Author: shashankmestry
Content:
How do we pass Uint256 arguments? Uint256 considers as 2 values. My constructor has following parameters
> (
>         name: felt,
>         symbol: felt,
>         initial_mint: Uint256
>     )
When I try to deploy it, it expects 4 parameters instead of 3

Author: milan3774
Content: as you write, Uint256 is 2 values, so you need to pass 4 in total to the constructor - split the initial_mint to "low" and "high" parts of a Uint256 struct https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/cairo/common/uint256.cairo#L9-L14

Author: shashankmestry
Content: So should I pass same value for low and high?

Author: milan3774
Content: no - `low` is the bottom 128 bits of the value, `high` is the upper 128 bits; so depends on what is the number you want to pass, I'm guessing it's less than 2**128, so you can just pass in the actual number and 0 for `high`

Author: shashankmestry
Content: Oh. Thanks a lot for such detailed explanation. Now I got the concept.

Author: calabashsquash
Content:
Yep so I know the commands required to deploy an account contract. I am asking how it is technically and economically possible to deploy an account contract without paying TX fees (which itself requires an account with funds to pay said fees). The entire point of TX fees is to appropriately deal with network congestion by allowing the market to adjust the cost of network participation. If you do not have TX fees for even just one aspect of the network, you're opening the network up to just get flooded with a bunch of noisey transactions (since they don't cost anything).

I'm aware that up until now, they just haven't enforced fees. This has been acceptable since the network is only in alpha. But as of today's update, fees are enforced. I am wondering how a TX that involves deploying a new account contract is executing without there being funds on that account contract to pay the TX fees.

Let me know if that still doesn't make sense and I'll try rewording again :)

Author: calabashsquash
Content: Someone explained a couple of the possible ways of solving this issue to me a while back, but I can't find those messages and I'm not sure which one was actually implemented

Author: laurip
Content:
As far as I've understood, there are two aspects to this:
1) I think even currently contract deployment is for free. Only regular transactions cost. Someone please correct if I'm wrong. This is not an issue in mainnet, since only whitelisted contracts can be deployed
2) Eventually, wallets will send the fees to the account contract address in advance, and sequencer takes it from there. The address can be calculated in advance, so that's not an issue. Wallets will probably take the deployment fee from the users as part of the user's first "real" transaction

Author: drspacemn#9574
Content:
As recursive proving on StarkNet and higher layers above L2 are rolled out, they will be predominately application specific(in similar ways that StarkEx applications are today)

So many of these details will be implementation details by the L3 operator. 

You will be able to prove valid execution the way StarkNet does to Ethereum today except that your L3 will be proving it to StarkNet.

Since you have control over the app design at this L3 layer I don't see an explicit need to add a layer above that(L4)

Content:
Hey that's really interesting but I am not sure to understand correctly. Could you please correct me?
If a program takes ``o(k)`` steps to be ran, its proof takes ``o(log(k))`` steps to be verified. So if you have a lot of proofs on L2, some people could decide to wait and generate a proof or their calculations together before submitting this "shared proof" to StarkNet which would restart the same process, so the final proof would be verified in ``o(log(log(k))``. Is this what is called a L3? As I understand it, scalability looks infinite because the more users there are the lower the cost per user. If we had an infinite number of users, would the final proof take o(log(log(log ... k ...))) steps to be proven, so 0 steps per user? If yes that's really nice for calculations, but what's the catch? Content: That's the power of Zero-Knowledge proofs. StarkNet doesn't employ private transactions, but at this higher level you could write the proving mechanism to omit the tx data and simply prove to the verifier(on L2) that it knows it. Therefore preserving the privacy of L3.

Author: prtk418
Content: Hey guys, wanted to know how long did it take you from learning cairo and all about starknet till deploying of a production dapp. Wanted to know this because I am putting together a time estimate for our project

Author: laurip
Content:
depends a lot on your background. If you, for example, have strong Ethereum dev background, things are much easier to understand. The language itself has some weirdness, but mostly understanding the environment is the trickiest part.
Currently one of the main challenges is also that everything is still changing very fast - something you wrote yesterday might not work anymore today. So you have to stay informed about many developments.
But if we forget about the changes part, and you have strong Ethereum background, you could code some small example contract with tests in maybe a month, from zero.

Author: lhadri
Content:
**Considering numbers:** 
For unsigned numbers the max value is P-1 [needs 252 bits]. 
For signed numbers the max positive value is (P-1 )/2 [needs 1 signed bit + 251 bits]. 
So in the two cases we need 252 bits to store values, but Cairo uses the second interpretation.

**Considering Texts:** 
248 bits are sufficient to store any 'Short string'. But since the unit of storage of Cairo is 252 bits, we have 1 signed bit + 3 unused bits + 248 bits.

Am I correct?

Author: merkle
Content: VsCode

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: `--wallet` is the name of the wallet provider, `--account` is the name of the account. We'll fix the documentation to be more explicit

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
Yes, except that P is very close to (and slightly above) `2^251`, so while you do need 252 bits to represent a value in the range `[0, P)`, a lot of the 252-bit integers cannot be represented.
For example, with a short string you have only 3 unused bits (rather than 1+3)

Content:
It looks like 0x0143c2b110961626f46c4b35c55fa565227ffdb803155e917df790bad29240b9 is a proxy contract, that tried to delegate call to class hash `0x8521bc76bbd3268e08ea796cb365fc2f4f8e224a7acdf72012faf1146fd14c`.

Hey frens

Stark budliers have to build data indexing services when data indexing services don't come to StarkNet. 

Checkpoint is a library to index StarkNet events and make them accessible through a GraphQL API. Checkpoint is heavily inspired by The Graph and aims to provide the same solution on StarkNet.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content: A full node can verify more if required. For example, it can reexecute the transactions and see all the intermediate states. The L1 verifier will only see the final diff of the block (in particular, it won't see the transactions) with a proof that there exist signed transactions that result in that diff

Author: 0xlenny#9579
Content: Hey üëã  Is there any way to calculate a deterministic contract address before deploy in Cairo ?

Author: gregoryguillou
Content: 1st 0.9.0 differentiate the class from the instance (i.e the contract). When you instantiate a contract, you use a salt so assuming you know the that salt, you can derive the contract address. That is the doc https://docs.starknet.io/docs/Contracts/contract-address and the code https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/ed6cf8d6cec50a6ad95fa36d1eb4a7f48538019e/src/starkware/starknet/services/api/gateway/contract_address.py#L12 . There is currently a discussion to make account address (which are also contracts) predictable so that the wallets can be compatibles https://community.starknet.io/t/account-keys-and-addresses-derivation-standard/1230 .

Author: 0xlenny#9579
Content: Many thanks for your reply üôè  I see this can be done off-chain, do you have any exemple on how to do it on-chain too ?

Author: gregoryguillou
Content: I do not know. I would say that generating a salt on chain is a challenge in itself and I have no clue of the security implication of someone being able to guess it or to access it when your transaction is pending.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
There are two reasons:
1. We don't have an "auction" mechanism for the fee at the moment
2. Collecting and running the transactions (before the proof generation starts) is not optimal (we improve it as we go)

The result is that when there is more tx than the TPS we currently handle for a significant period of time, there's a queue of txs that starts to grow and the time to complete a new tx starts to increase

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
Ok i see a few problems here :PES_CoolNerd: 
`let market : Market = market_support.read(address)`
should be 
`let (market : Market) = market_support.read(address)` 
because every cairo function returns a tuple even if it's a single element
then assert doesn't work like that you should read this https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/consts.html#the-assert-statement-and-compound-expressions

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
> and the entrypoint selector 0x15d40a3d6ca2ac30f4031e42be28da9b056fef9bb7357ac5e85627ee876e5ad is nowhere to be found
The contract `0x691bd65ac65f3d6b9001fe864246270d561ef95798e2b7d38dd7090bd201e4b` is a proxy that only has the `__default__` entrypoint. The default entrypoint delegates call to the `__execute__` selector in the account contract class

Content: this is what happens here https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-contracts-starknet/blob/5ab151828443421bb4f03e53f2d69e986be181ab/contracts/Proxy.cairo#L53

Content:
Function calls have to be in a separate line. `assert uint256_lt(market.min_amount, amount) = 1` doesn't work you have to go like this:
```py
let (is_lt) = uint256_lt(market.min_amount, amount)
assert is_lt = 1
```

Author: mecnhayk
Content: The k'th column is g(k,X^1000), and the k'th  row is g(x,k^1000).  g was constructed in such a way that if f(x) = x^n +... then g(x,y) = (x^n%1000)(x^1000*(n/1000))+... So if n<10^6 then rows and columns are <1000.

Author: zkthor#0560
Content: and how does the L2 block correspond to what is sent to L1? Is it that all transactions in the L2 block are sent in one transaction to L1

Author: laurip
Content:
it's not really a full blockchain, but something similar to it.
I'm not sure, but I think the concept of 'block' in starknet is just something the sequencer chooses as a batch of transactions, but it doesn't have much other meaningful semantics.  I'm also not sure if one block is rolled up as one transaction to L1, or multiple.

Author: catalytic__converter
Content:
what data do you want to shield? Think of a traditional arrangement where to abide by your contractual obligation you have to provide some data. Now you don't need to, you can provide a proof of it happening so whoever you are complying with doesn't have extra data to resell.

Applications:
- verifying employment for rental/loan
- on-chain credit score
- computation on private medical data
- consensus between IoT nodes

await deployer.invoke(wETHContract, "approve", {spender: jediSwapRouterContract.address, amount: uint256.bnToUint256("1000000000000000000")})```

Content: Just in case my stupidity can be put to good use for others. The problem was I had some mock contract with the same name and at the import level of an intermediate testing contract I was importing the namespace from the mock (that's what you get when you reuse testing files carelessly), which wasn't updated, as it was a pending task. Mr. Ockham would have something to say about me looking for a complex solution to a trival problem...

Author: joshklop
Content:
Based on my understanding, the process to update the state on L1 currently looks something like this:
1. "Continuous memory pages" are individually sent to the MemoryPageFactRegistry as calldata
2. Portions of the memory pages are sent to the GpsVerifier, which registers a "fact" upon verification
3. The programs output is sent to the main Starknet contract, which verifies that the fact from (2) was indeed registered and advances the state by one block

Content:
What is the diff between public key and contract address of a starknet account contract? I deployed a new account and got both:
```
Sent deploy account contract transaction.

NOTE: This is a modified version of the OpenZeppelin account contract. The signature is computed
differently.

Contract address: 0x05e20bad7ea9a3ec52f8ee69b6d3bb5b39726a5858ccf1f9b84cda556754c6ad
Public key: 0x06db0cd08031720c368503771bb94ea3c05c628c0ab28f16218c713427169aad
Transaction hash: 0x24da8fa05df817dbe033cac3de197480df008a389cca8dbd25a21fb18e028f9
```
I think it has something to do with account abstraction but could you ELI5? Thx üöÄ

Author: _dsi
Content:
So Ethereum if I'm not mistaken, this mechanism is builtin in the private key. Your private key is derived to get your public key and the funds held by this public/private keypair.

On Starknet you have the same mechanism of public/private keypair except that they give you access to a specific smart contract (actually it could give you access to many smart contracts if they had the same private key).

Author: _dsi
Content: Hope that made sense

Author: whatthedev
Content: Thank you, yes makes sense! As a follow-up...In Ethereum, I think your public key is hashed to create your wallet address. In Starknet is your public key similarly used to create your contract address(es), or are these independent?

Author: _dsi
Content:
Yeah I remember reading something like for Ethereum, the public key is not the address of the wallet so I think it's true.
For StarkNet contracts, I'm pretty sure it's independent, the private/public keyPair is unrelated to the generated contract address. You can basically set any private key on any account contract

Author: eni7912
Content:
> 
> Pure and view functions actually do cost gas. But by calling them via RPC only your local node has to do the calculation and therefore the gas cost is simulated.
> 
> If a deployed contract calls these functions everyone in the network has to do the calculation and therefore they do have to cost gas.
> 
https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/questions/49253/does-view-functions-cost-gas-and-how-to-send-transaction-in-a-proper-way

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
The OS is the Cairo program that is being proven and verified on-chain.
The sequencer doesn't need it to simulate the transactions. All it needs is to implement the system calls. After a block is closed, the sequencer runs the OS on the transactions and creates a proof for this run. This proof is verified on-chain.

Author: Lior Goldberg#6041
Content:
No, the storage consists only of felts (and other things that consists of felts themselves). Storing a pointer as-is doesn't make sense, since it points to a valid place only within the transaction. Once the transaction ends it will no longer point to anything useful.

(Storing an array (pointer + length) is another thing and we intend to support it in the future)

Author: udayj.
Content:
`func get_num_valid_sig{syscall_ptr : felt*, 
    pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*, range_check_ptr, ecdsa_ptr: SignatureBuiltin*}(
    num_left_to_validate: felt, num_validated: felt, hash:felt, sig: Signature*, 
    pubkey: felt*, pubkey_whitelister_adddress: felt) -> (res: felt):

    if num_left_to_validate == 0:
        return(num_validated)
    end

    let (is_whitelisted) = IPubkeyWhitelister.is_whitelisted(pubkey_whitelister_adddress, [pubkey])

    if is_whitelisted == 1:

        SignatureVerification.verify_sig(hash, [pubkey], [sig])
        return get_num_valid_sig(num_left_to_validate - 1, 
                                num_validated + 1, 
                                hash, 
                                sig + Signature.SIZE,
                                pubkey + 1,
                                pubkey_whitelister_adddress)
    else:

        return get_num_valid_sig(num_left_to_validate - 1, 
                                num_validated, 
                                hash, 
                                sig + Signature.SIZE,
                                pubkey + 1,
                                pubkey_whitelister_adddress)
    end
end`

Author: udayj.
Content:
this is how the flow is:-

1. call execute method of account contract (A)
2. Account contract (A) calls the actual contract (B) using call_contract syscall
3. Contract B internally calls a recursive function which uses verify_ecdsa_signature calls multiple times
4. Contract B then calls another contract C using call_contract syscall and returns the retdata to account contract A

Author: catalytic__converter
Content:
What is the correct way of doing it?

I'm getting the same error after I try to write to a `@storage_var` inside an if statment.

I can fix it by adding `return()` at the end, but it then exits the function prematurely.

Actually fixed it by adding at the end of my if and else cases:

```    tempvar syscall_ptr :felt* = syscall_ptr
    tempvar pedersen_ptr :HashBuiltin* = pedersen_ptr
    tempvar range_check_ptr: felt = range_check_ptr```

To match each of my implicit arguments in the function declaration.

Author: bowlofchilli
Content:
refering to this part of documentation -> Handling method calls
As with most StarkNet contracts, interacting with a proxy contract requires an account abstraction. One notable difference with proxy contracts versus other contract implementations is that calling @view methods also requires an account abstraction. As of now, direct calls to default entrypoints are only supported by StarkNet's syscalls from other contracts i.e. account contracts. The differences in getter methods written in Python, for example, are as follows:
# standard ERC20 call
result = await erc20.totalSupply().call()

# upgradeable ERC20 call
result = await signer.send_transaction(
        account, PROXY.contract_address, 'totalSupply', []
    )

Author: aybehrouz
Content:
(moving the post from #‚ú®ÔΩústarknet )
I would like to thank you for the STARK Math series. They are really helpful and they are helping me to (almost üòÖ) understand STARKS.

However, I think this particular article (https://medium.com/starkware/arithmetization-ii-403c3b3f4355) forgets to express an important point. It seems to me that besides the composition polynomial, the Reed-Solomon encoding of the trace (called `f` in the article) also needs to pass the low-degree testing.

Author: aybehrouz
Content:
We know that when we have a low degree polynomial `p(x)` and we calculate `g(x) = p(x) / (x - a)`, if `p(a) = 0` then
`g(x)` would be a polynomial of degree less than `deg(p) - 1`. If `p(a) != 0` then `g(x)` will be a rational function which is far from any **low degree** polynomial. However if `p(x)` is not a polynomial when `p(x) != 0`, `g(x)` will not be a rational function and it can be close to a low degree polynomial by choosing `p` appropriately.

So I suppose when we are testing the composition polynomial we should run the low-degree testing for `f` to make sure the numerator of the composition polynomial is a low degree polynomial. However, still there could be a problem. Low degree testing can only assure that `f` is not far from a polynomial, but it can not guarantee that `f` is a low degree polynomial. Back to our simple example, if `p(x)` is close to a low degree polynomial (but is not a polynomial), can we say that `p(x) / (x - a)` will be far from any low degree polynomial when `p(a) != 0`?

Author: aybehrouz
Content: What could be a good reference to read more about this subject?

Author: aybehrouz
Content:
and another question...
Could combining STARK verification and normal replay verification be beneficial in practice? I know that STARK verification is exponentially faster. But like when insertion sort is faster than heap sort for small arrays, Can mixing normal and STARK verification increase the performance? Or should we just try to batch computation as much as we can and then generate a single proof for the final state transition?

Author: Deleted User
Content: Hello guys, a few months ago back when I discovered cairo, I remember reading something like "storage is expensive, computation is cheap, so you should replace storage by computation when you can, e.g. with a bloom filter". But how can a bloom filter be cheaper on StarkNet since you pay for changes? You will still add some bits when blacklisting a value, so you will still have to pay for a rewrite, won't you?

Author: Deleted User
Content: I'm curious to hear your thoughts @sam, I saw you implemented one

Author: _sam___
Content:
I was mainly using that as a test project to (naively) implement when learning Cairo, after reading RoboTeddy's article of advice. Haven't actually done much production Cairo that would warrant a bloom filter

It likely only makes sense for a small subset of problems ‚Äî since you need to adjust the bloom filter parameters depending on your use case (false positive probability & capacity of the set)

Though, thinking more about it now after your question... I think you're right. It likely would not make sense as a dynamic data structure that you can add members to from a contract. Since you'd probably want to pack the bits into a single storage slot, and if any of those bits change you'd get charged for that whole change right?

Author: Deleted User
Content: Yeah afaik

Author: _sam___
Content: However I could see there being value in a static bloom filter. Maybe some big allowlist for your mint

Author: Deleted User
Content: The problem I'm thinking of comes from @Cchalop1 who wants to build a voting system on StarkNet

Author: Deleted User
Content: So he would have a storage_var (vote_id, vote_option) -> (votes_amount) that counts the votes

Author: Deleted User
Content: but he also needs a way to blacklist people who voted (for a vote or for a vote and an option if he wants to allow them to chose multiple options)

Author: Deleted User
Content: The naive way to do it would be (vote_id) -> (address), but I just remembered that bloom filters where designed for this kind of blacklist problem

Author: _sam___
Content:
Yeah as a data structure to dynamically add members to, my gut reaction (after the realization above) is i don't think it'd be worth using a bloom filter for that on StarkNet.

If the allow/deny-list was static and can be posted on chain in advance of a vote then it might make sense, but for this I don't think so.

Probably better off trying to figure out how you can combine the vote & vote permissions into one. Maybe look into how snapshot is going about it (think they're still building on StarkNet but idk for sure)

array is a pointer to a memory cell so when you do `array=array+1` you just point to the next memory cell, which is the next value in the array

Author: tokyoswap
Content:
hi
is possibile to use cairo for proving something in another blockchain
?
like i take a balance from polygon and want verify it (in some way)

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Cairo is blockchain oblivious, and in fact not even necessarily blockchain related. It's a language that allows writing provable programs (in the sense that their execution is provable). That said, there are several ways to interpret your question
1. In StarkNet, where the smart contracts are written in Cairo, can I prove things about the state of other chains, like my balance in Polygon. The short answer is yes, but that's not necessarily Cairo-related. As long as you have some bridging from that chain, e.g. a contract that holds the state commitment of Polygon, you can verify things against it (e.g. via storage proofs).
2. You can use Cairo to potentially make the above verifications easier by submitting to a Cairo verifier contract in StarkNet a proof that says something about the state of Polygon, given some commitment. You can then compare that commitment against what's stored in the Polygon bridge contract.
3. You can do the above in any chain, as long as you have some Cairo verifier contract that you can submit proofs to.

Author: itisok
Content:
## **Estimating the Transaction Fee**

Before running the actual transaction, we need to estimate the associated fee.

```jsx

starknet estimate_fee --address 0x7394cbe418daa16e42b87ba67372d4ab4a5df0b05c6e554d158458ce245bc10 --network alpha-goerli --function mint --abi erc20_abi.json --inputs 0xcd70196a5edc2bd5c903c63fb3c119db1a2b10013d820434eb4be0245d623d 100000000000000000000 0
```

If all goes well, we get the estimated fee in the format of:

`The estimated fee is: 12542835995664 WEI (0.000013 ETH).`

Since this is an estimate, we will markup 50%, and use it as max fee for the transaction:

`echo "12542835995664*1.5" | bc`

   `18814253993496.0`

## **Executing the Transaction**

Finally, we are ready!

```jsx
starknet invoke --address 0x7394cbe418daa16e42b87ba67372d4ab4a5df0b05c6e554d158458ce245bc10 --network alpha-goerli --function mint --abi erc20_abi.json --max_fee 18814253993496 --inputs 0xcd70196a5edc2bd5c903c63fb3c119db1a2b10013d820434eb4be0245d623d 100000000000000000000 0

```

Author: grillo.eth
Content:
Hello everyone. I have a few questions about StarkNet execution limits and timeouts. It's somewhat long to explain, but I'll do my best to be brief. I've been working for some time now on a game design pattern where 2+ players compete completely off-chain in a fully P2P fashion, and, once a winner is decided, the whole match is verified on-chain. The game flow was supposed to work like this:
1) A player would create a room on-chain. He would provide a new public key just for that match.
2) A second player would joins the room on-chain, providing his own public key.
3) At this moment, a random number was to be created. From this number, a map, some items and starting positions could be derived, but not stored on-chain: my idea was to use** a view function with the random seed as input, and the whole initial game state as the output**.
4) Players would connect through the frontend and exchange signed turns via WebRTC (fully P2P). They would store the whole chain of signed turns locally until one of them won.
5) The winner would then be able to call an external function, providing the whole set of turns. Each turn would be verified on-chain (the whole game logic is written in a state transition view function) and, if the player was actually the winner, the game would be closed.

Author: grillo.eth
Content: Now, I have come a long way building this, but I could only recently begin to test the view functions and long loops required for this design to work. I was of the idea that execution on StarkNet was cheap, so it wouldn't be a problem. And asking some questions here and there, most people didn't find a problem with the design pattern.

Author: grillo.eth
Content: Well, the thing is, I cannot even make the initial_state function run correctly, that I'm getting timeouts and functions with `Error: End of program was not reached`. Now, I know my code is not fully optimized and that I could make it more efficient, but if the first function is not able to run, I doubt I'll be able to run that, together with a whole bunch of turns, to verify a winning game.

The image below shows the process, and I have verified the functions are working correctly, running them separately in parallel with javascript code. They produce something like this:

Content: Noise grids of different size, which are added together, then multiplied by a shape grid to produce a result.

Author: grillo.eth
Content:
Well, having said all of this, my questions:
1) Is there a limit on the amount of code that can be executed by a view function? Is this an RPC issue that I could solve by having my own StarkNet node?
2) I tried making an external state-changing function call the view function to check if it would work that way (maybe if I paid for gas, the code would finish execution). But even then I got the `Error: End of program was not reached` error.
3) Could this be a testnet/alpha issue? Maybe this desing might work in the future? I was of the idea that I could optimize for execution, and verifying thousands of turns, looping through every one of them, didn't sound like crazy when talking to some more knowledgeable people.
4) Is there anything I'm missing? Anything I could try or any repo I should check out?

Author: Deleted User
Content: I think you can have two designs. The easiest one would be a ``__delegated_execute__`` function which just asks a signature as a parameter and can be called by anyone. That way the transaction would be paid by the account which calls you automatically (but then that means you are not the one sending the transaction and you need an interaction with someone). The one that is being working one requires changing the protocol if I understood correctly and works with a paymaster. Basically you can allow someone to spend your funds to send his transactions, the cool thing is the logic is ran on chain so you don't need to interact in real time with someone.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: TLDR is that this alone doesn't allow it. Rougly you can divide account abstraction into three, "signature abstraction", "replay protection abstraction" (or nonce abstraction), and "fee abstraction". Currently we only have the first and decided for now that we won't have the second (protocol level nonce). The third will come in the future via the paymaster mechanism (see the account-abstraction part 2 post in Shamans)

Fees
We proceed to incorporate fees into StarkNet, making them mandatory (first on Testnet, and later also on Mainnet) for `invoke` transactions. The `declare` transaction will not require fees at this point. Author: abishekbashyal
Content:

I was working on implementing a **FRI prover** based on vitalik's blog on ZK -Stark :StarkNet:  part 3 i.e. STARKs, Part 3: Into the Weeds
https://vitalik.ca/general/2018/07/21/starks_part_3.html

Author: abishekbashyal
Content:
Confusion I've is:
During the implementation given the original points xs and its evaluation P(x) how can we recover each row polynomial ?? How to know given point was from row1 or row2 polynomial ??

In the code implementation:https://github.com/ethereum/research/blob/35ddfc7d8640d33367030b3c5f473709c45c90e3/mimc_stark/fri.py#L38
It was implemented as:

Author: abishekbashyal
Content:
```py
# Calculate the "column" at that x coordinate
    # (see https://vitalik.ca/general/2017/11/22/starks_part_2.html)
    # We calculate the column by Lagrange-interpolating each row, and not
    # directly from the polynomial, as this is more efficient
    quarter_len = len(xs)//4
    x_polys = f.multi_interp_4(
        [[xs[i+quarter_len*j] for j in range(4)] for i in range(quarter_len)],
        [[values[i+quarter_len*j] for j in range(4)] for i in range(quarter_len)]

Author: udayj.
Content:
the process_single_element function in fast_pedersen_hash.py got changed in the recent version

earlier the check being done was
assert element < FIELD_PRIME, "Element integer value >= FIELD_PRIME"

now the check is
assert 0 <= element < FIELD_PRIME, "Element integer value is out of range"
@Lucas | StarkWare @Lior Goldberg  just wanted to understand why this change was done ?

Author: AlgoCratz- DaThmm#0102
Content: Check your dm's once you see this

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: the error message is shorter now as for the reason i'm not sure there is a deep one

Author: udayj.
Content: yes earlier negative numbers were allowed but now it has to be a positive integer - i am not very knowledgeable in finite field math so maybe @Lior Goldberg can comment

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: everything is modulo P a big prime so -1 = P - 1 which is positive

Author: udayj.
Content:
when calculating a message hash for signing, compute_hash_on_elements was being called which in turn called fast_pedersen_hash where the check was element <FIELD_PRIME . however, now this same function is checking for positive integers - this is python code - and negative numbers were working earlier when hashing

does this mean now we need to do the modular arithmetic in the python code and then send the value for hashing ? Is it due to some compiler change where earlier this function was doing the modular arithmetic before hashing ?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: yes, as for the reason i don't think it's linked to the compiler

Author: udayj.
Content: ok thanks....still would be good to know why this change was done

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: it was a bug

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
Hello, 

1. I have developed `addDeployTransaction` with Go 
2. when I deploy the OZ account that was running with v0.9 (i.e. v0.3.2 with the get_nonce, former syntax, etc). I get hit with  https://community.starknet.io/t/while-deploying-code-i-get-the-error/1294/4 . 
3. reproduce the exact same pb with `starknet-js` and fixed it as explained with `json` package. It looks like the problem comes from the way data are stored inside the .json output of the compile and the goal of the `json` is to manage the BigNumber format.
4. On the other hand I do not have the issue with the latest OZ 0.4.0b account and Cairo compiler v0.10. 

I have 2 questions:
-  Has the problem been fixed somehow by the compiler or the file format or have I just been lucky and the problem is still?
- If not, is there some details somewhere of that exact problem so that I can implement a solution that I understand?

Thank your for your help!

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
I found the answers: to my questions
- The file has number that are > than max uint64 in it and are not stored as string but as number. It is valid JSON
- Go has the same problem as JS by default, i.e. it turns those numbers into float64 and the values are altered

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Can you try to be more specific? The question "how the proof is verified" is essentially a broad "how STARKs work" question. For this I can refer you to Eli's recent tweet collecting links to different overviews in different levels https://twitter.com/EliBenSasson/status/1578380154476208131?s=20&t=eZHjqMdGXRoZ5kqtUQtoNA.

Re "How several requests are batched together", instead of proving that P_1, P_2 executed successfully, I prove that a different program P that takes as input the code of P_1,P_2 and simulates them, executed successfully (P is a universal Cairo program, i.e. it knows how to execute given programs)

Author: sa.bur.o
Content:
Hey guys I was just following the starknet-edu tutorial on Account abstraction
Not quite sure how to use it in real world scenario, so is this workflow correct?

1. I deploy a special account contract with features I need (e.g. multicall)
2. Users communicate with my dapp using that single account contract as a single entrypoint
3. Users on frontend invoke functions in my contracts from the account contract (not directly from wallets)

Author: milan3774
Content:
you, as a protocol builder, don't deploy a account contract - that's the role of wallet providers like Argent, Braavos, Ledger and that's what StarkNet users will use to interact with your contracts

all of accounts already have multicall built in, so you can take advantage of in on the frontend - stack as many TX as you want (as long as your within execution limits) in whatever way it makes sense for you

`get_caller_address` will return the address of the wallet/account contract your users are using

Author: sa.bur.o
Content: Thank you for a prompt reply! What if I would need something more custom like multisig or gas abstraction?

Author: milan3774
Content: yeah, for multisig you'd need to create your own account contract (there might be some open source implementation around); for gas abstraction, that's still TBD I believe, but might be supported by wallet providers

Author: sa.bur.o
milan3774
Content: sorry, can't tell what's wrong with the code; auth is commonly done using ownable or access control libs, but for that to work, you'll need to have `get_caller_address` not return 0 üò∞

Author: _andrew#7540
Content:
Hey, @Remi! Yes, tokenIds should not be assumed to follow any pattern as described by EIP721: "...callers SHALL NOT assume that ID numbers have any specific pattern to them, and MUST treat the ID as a ‚Äúblack box‚Äù. "

See "NFT Identifiers" in https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-721

To your point, I know a good amount of erc721 implementations just increment.

Author: t4or
Content: Oh, I got it. Thank you very much for your reply. Maybe it could be cool to have a section on the documentation to explain how can we use a token contract in cairo with incremental id as it's done for the solidity version

Author: t4or
Content: I think it could be very useful for people looking to port their nft collection to starknet because most of the collections have mint functions with an incremental id

Author: _andrew#7540
Content:
Yeah, definitely! It‚Äôs probably worth making a general `Counters` library‚Äîand maybe adding it to an erc721 preset with updated docs üôÇ

Would you like to create the issue?

https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/issues/new

Author: t4or
Content: Sure I will

Author: 0xmur
Content:
I want to ask some question about the account contract question:
how does the `__validate__` and `__execute__` work?

The `__validate__` is for the StarkNet OS to run it first, and if it is successful, then run `__execute__`?

Or the `__validate__` is just for the some Dev. Tool to check the current call which we will send will be work?
Ôºàe.g. `sendTransaction` will check the tx by `__validate__` in local?Ôºâ

Author: 0xcoburn
Content: validate runs first and if its succesful execute is called, if its not successful the tx is rejected

Author: 0xmur
Content: Hence the StarkNet Os will check it with `__validate__` when OS receive a call sent from account contract?

Author: 0xcoburn
Content: correct

Author: 0xmur
Content: Thanks a lot!!

Content: Hi guys! Want a report small bug during deployment smart contract to testnet

Author: favela021
Content:
1. Was following official documentation
2. At "declare contract" step got an error "Requested contract address 0x68... is not deployed"
3. Tried deploy my account again but got "Account '__default__' for network 'alpha-goerli' is already deployed."

Author: favela021
Content: Deployment account transaction failed, but account was marked as "deployed" anyway. So, I couldn't declare a contract

Author: favela021
Content: The solution for me was open ~/.starknet_accounts/starknet_open_zeppelin_accounts.json and replace "deployed" true to false and then deploy account / declare contract again

Author: favela021
Content: hope it will help to someone

Author: Deleted User
Content:
Cairo was designed to allow efficient proofs generation and verification, you can lear more about it here: https://www.cairo-lang.org/cairo-whitepaper/
felt means field element, the Field used by Starknet is of size ``2^251+17‚ãÖ2^192+1``, so a felt can be represented using 252 bits (but you can only store ~251 bits of data in a felt)

Author: carter2233
Content: Hello sirs, I want to ask how can we confirm a transaction is confirmed and can't be rollbacked ? The field "status" in the transaction detail will takes 10+ hours to became "ACCEPTED_ON_L1", is there another way to insure if a transaction be valid?

Author: wind.rider
Content: Ser, when the transaction is in pending status, then it'll not be rollbacked (pls check screenshot), and this link will be helpful : https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/Blocks/transaction-life-cycle/ thank you

Author: carter2233
Content: So if a transaction is accepted on L2, can we think it has been successed?

Author: wind.rider
Content: Yes, ser, but if L1 finality is required, then the status needs to be accepted on l1,it's just that usually the transaction will not be rollback when it becomes pending status, thank youü§ù

Content: Thanks, I'll study the documents more.

Author: closer2282
Content:
Here‚Äòre our suggestions: it's okay just to deploy currently using Cairo 0.x using the Proxy pattern and then upgrade to Cairo 1.0 while preserving the state of their smart contract. 
Cairo will keep improving over time but after Cairo 1.0 the changes should be backward compatible so it wouldn't be mandatory to upgrade
And these articles are worthy to read
https://community.starknet.io/t/regenesis-state-migration-current-suggestion/2080
https://community.starknet.io/t/launch-safely-over-starknet-minding-the-regenesis-plan/2409

Author: M10#5504
Content: Hello, I am trying to implement a 2-player tictactoe game on Starknet where 2 players join, stake a certain amount of ETH and then the winner obtains a prize. What is the equivalent of ```payable(address).transfer(amt)``` in Cairo/Starknet contracts?

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser, there is no equivalent in StarkNet. There is no native currency in StarkNet; every token is an ERC20.
So they need to call the transfer() or trasnferFrom() function from the deployed eth Token thank youüôèüèª

Author: neo764
Content:
Hi, could you help me with the concept of my application and share your opinion if such flow is possible or not;)
I am setting up a startup that is going to use Cairo language to prove that operations executed off-chain, that changes the on-chain smart-contract's state are legit.
I have simplified my scenario and there are 2 simple parts of my proof of concept:

1. My first step is to create an solidity contract that will act as a simple treasury, that means it will only store the balances of users and will have 3 methods 'deposit' (transacted by user), 'withdraw' (transacted by user) and 'change' (transacted by Cairo code with valid proof).
2. Cairo program that based on input data and current state, transfers balance from one account to another deducting a little fee and adding it to the chosen account. I want to aggregate this simple Cairo executions (transactions) and after some number (for example 100) of such executions/transactions, aggregate them into one state change/delta, aggregate traces and generate proof. Then transact smart-contract's 'change' method  and pass state change and proof to it. Then the method is going to verify based on the provided proof if such state change is valid, and if so apply this state change to the current state

Thank you in advance for any ideas;)

Content: hello guys I'm trying to deploy  an ERC-721 with protostar and I am supposed to input a name, symbol,... But inputs are only decimals. How do I input a name in decimals ?

Author: milan3774
Content:
Cairo encodes short strings into a felt (number), see https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/consts.html#short-string-literals

you can use for example this py function to conver a string to a number:

```
def str_to_felt(text: str) -> int:
    b_text = bytes(text, "ascii")
    return int.from_bytes(b_text, "big")
```

there's also an online tool somewhere, but I can't remember the address right now üò¶
